1
00:00:19,641 --> 00:00:23,145
From the silence

2
00:00:23,228 --> 00:00:26,774
From the night

3
00:00:26,857 --> 00:00:30,152
Comes a distant

4
00:00:30,235 --> 00:00:34,281
Lullaby

5
00:00:36,575 --> 00:00:39,787
Soul
Surrendering your soul

6
00:00:39,828 --> 00:00:43,373
The heart in you not whole

7
00:00:43,457 --> 00:00:47,169
For love

8
00:00:47,252 --> 00:00:51,632
For love

9
00:00:54,760 --> 00:01:00,599
Walked out

10
00:01:00,682 --> 00:01:06,063
Cast into the dark

11
00:01:08,065 --> 00:01:15,155
Branded with a mark

12
00:01:15,197 --> 00:01:18,992
Of shame

13
00:01:19,076 --> 00:01:24,665
Of Cain

14
00:01:28,252 --> 00:01:30,462
[Man Narrating]
If I could just go back.

15
00:01:31,588 --> 00:01:33,966
If I could rub everything out,

16
00:01:34,049 --> 00:01:36,093
starting with myself.

17
00:01:38,053 --> 00:01:40,681
Starting with borrowing
a jacket.

18
00:01:40,764 --> 00:01:44,518
Oh, such fleeting
paradise

19
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:48,188
Such innocent
delight

20
00:01:48,272 --> 00:01:52,818
To love

21
00:01:52,901 --> 00:01:55,696
Be loved

22
00:01:55,779 --> 00:02:00,617
A lullaby

23
00:02:01,702 --> 00:02:10,002
Then silence

24
00:02:13,464 --> 00:02:16,633
- [ Woman ] Frances, that was lovely.
- I'm so glad. Thank you.

25
00:02:16,717 --> 00:02:19,470
[ Man ]
Congratulations.

26
00:02:19,553 --> 00:02:22,222
Marvelous.
Most enjoyable.

27
00:02:22,264 --> 00:02:24,767
Herbert Greenleaf.
My wife, Emily.

28
00:02:24,850 --> 00:02:26,268
Thank you.
Tom Ripley.

29
00:02:26,351 --> 00:02:28,687
- How do you do ?
- You were at Princeton.

30
00:02:28,771 --> 00:02:31,648
Most likely you'll know our son,
Dick. Dickie Greenleaf.

31
00:02:31,732 --> 00:02:33,650
[Emily] I couldn't help
noticing your jacket.

32
00:02:33,734 --> 00:02:35,486
Yes.

33
00:02:35,569 --> 00:02:38,614
Class of'56.

34
00:02:38,697 --> 00:02:41,533
How is Dickie ?

35
00:02:41,617 --> 00:02:43,952
[Frances]
We've enjoyed meeting you.

36
00:02:44,036 --> 00:02:46,538
I do hope that you'll
come out and see us.

37
00:02:46,622 --> 00:02:49,625
- Thank you. That's very kind.
- Both of you.

38
00:02:49,708 --> 00:02:52,836
- Herbert ?
- Yes, yes. I very much hope so.

39
00:02:52,920 --> 00:02:56,090
Of course, Dickie's idea
of music is jazz.

40
00:02:56,173 --> 00:02:58,509
- Oh, dear.
- He has a saxophone.

41
00:02:58,592 --> 00:03:01,553
To my ear,
jazz is just noise.

42
00:03:01,637 --> 00:03:03,764
Just an insolent noise.

43
00:03:03,806 --> 00:03:06,809
- Very nice to meet you.
- And you.

44
00:03:06,850 --> 00:03:08,769
- Sir.
- We'll see you at the shipyard.

45
00:03:08,852 --> 00:03:10,771
- I hope to.
- Good.

46
00:03:12,397 --> 00:03:14,650
I have to run !
I'm very late !

47
00:03:16,485 --> 00:03:19,488
- Ah, you were great !
- You were great.

48
00:03:19,571 --> 00:03:22,282
Darling couple,
aren't they ?

49
00:03:22,324 --> 00:03:25,369
Yes, they are.
Exceptional young man.

50
00:03:27,579 --> 00:03:29,832
- Thanks a lot for the jacket.
- Thanks for filling in for me.

51
00:03:29,915 --> 00:03:32,000
Take care of that wrist.
Bye, Fran.

52
00:03:39,591 --> 00:03:42,511
Believe me.
Buy I.B.M. now, before it splits.

53
00:03:42,594 --> 00:03:44,513
You'll make yourself
a fortune.

54
00:03:44,596 --> 00:03:46,515
You think so ?

55
00:03:46,598 --> 00:03:49,601
[ Chattering, indistinct ]

56
00:04:12,207 --> 00:04:14,835
[Piano]

57
00:04:22,801 --> 00:04:24,720
Sorry.
Sorry.

58
00:04:25,846 --> 00:04:27,765
Sorry.

59
00:04:27,848 --> 00:04:31,185
[Mr. Greenleaf] Youĺve probably
heard Dickie's been living in Italy.

60
00:04:31,268 --> 00:04:33,979
Mongibello.
South of Naples.

61
00:04:34,062 --> 00:04:36,273
No kind of place
at all.

62
00:04:36,356 --> 00:04:38,275
- Good morning, sir.
- Frank.

63
00:04:38,358 --> 00:04:41,695
Marge,
his young lady,

64
00:04:41,737 --> 00:04:43,947
is supposedly writing
some kind of book.

65
00:04:44,031 --> 00:04:45,949
God only knows
what he does.

66
00:04:46,033 --> 00:04:50,037
By all accounts, they spend the whole
time on the beach or in a sailboat.

67
00:04:50,120 --> 00:04:53,582
That's my son's talent--
spending his allowance.

68
00:04:53,665 --> 00:04:57,002
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy, Tom ?

69
00:04:57,086 --> 00:05:00,380
Persuade my son
to come home ?

70
00:05:01,924 --> 00:05:03,842
I'd pay you...

71
00:05:03,926 --> 00:05:06,845
a thousand dollars.

72
00:05:09,098 --> 00:05:12,684
Well, I have always wanted
to go to Europe, sir, but--

73
00:05:12,768 --> 00:05:16,605
Good. Now you can go
for a reason.

74
00:05:16,688 --> 00:05:20,526
[Man Vocalizing]

75
00:05:24,279 --> 00:05:28,117
[Jazz ]

76
00:05:32,037 --> 00:05:34,415
Count Basie.

77
00:05:34,498 --> 00:05:37,751
Duke Ellington ?
I don't know.

78
00:05:39,753 --> 00:05:42,131
I don't know.

79
00:05:44,091 --> 00:05:46,385
I don't know.

80
00:05:52,516 --> 00:05:54,810
Dizzy Gillespie.

81
00:05:54,893 --> 00:05:58,313
My funny Valentine

82
00:05:58,397 --> 00:06:00,274
My funny Valentine.

83
00:06:00,315 --> 00:06:04,570
- [Man, Woman Arguing.: Faint]
-Sweet, funny Valentine

84
00:06:04,653 --> 00:06:07,364
I don't even know
if this is a man or a woman.

85
00:06:07,448 --> 00:06:12,202
-[Continues]
- [Crashing]

86
00:06:12,286 --> 00:06:14,496
[Arguing Continues]

87
00:06:25,507 --> 00:06:27,509
Charlie Parker ?

88
00:06:27,551 --> 00:06:30,429
Charlie Parker.
I know it. It's Bird.

89
00:06:33,015 --> 00:06:35,267
Yes !

90
00:06:35,350 --> 00:06:37,269
-[Ends]
- Ugh.

91
00:06:58,665 --> 00:07:01,752
- Here. I'll take it.
- Thanks.

92
00:07:01,835 --> 00:07:03,962
That thousand bucks
should come in handy.

93
00:07:04,046 --> 00:07:06,006
- Yes, sir.
- I'll get that.

94
00:07:10,677 --> 00:07:15,307
- Thank you.
- Sir. You're gonna have a great trip.

95
00:07:15,390 --> 00:07:18,268
Mr. Greenleaf is personal
friends with the Cunard people.

96
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:21,897
[Opera.: German]

97
00:07:23,857 --> 00:07:27,736
I can tell you, the Greenleaf name
opens a lot of doors.

98
00:07:49,967 --> 00:07:52,052
[ Horn Sounding ]

99
00:08:02,813 --> 00:08:04,690
[Man Speaking Italian
Over P.A. ]

100
00:08:04,773 --> 00:08:08,610
- [Ripley] Do you speak English ?
- [Man] What you name, please ?

101
00:08:08,694 --> 00:08:10,946
- Ripley.
- Follow me. No problem.

102
00:08:11,029 --> 00:08:13,907
- Here, Signor Ripley.
- Okay.

103
00:08:15,117 --> 00:08:17,035
Uh, there.
That one.

104
00:08:17,119 --> 00:08:19,204
- This one.
- Wait, is that all ? Count them.

105
00:08:19,288 --> 00:08:22,416
Attenzione.
Just one suitcase, Signor Ripley ?

106
00:08:22,458 --> 00:08:25,753
- Si.
- Attenzione.

107
00:08:31,049 --> 00:08:33,135
[ Man Speaking Italian ]

108
00:08:35,971 --> 00:08:38,724
[ Italian ]

109
00:08:41,185 --> 00:08:43,604
- What's your secret ?
- Excuse me ?

110
00:08:43,687 --> 00:08:46,815
No, itĺs just that--
You are American, aren't you ?

111
00:08:46,899 --> 00:08:48,984
No, itĺs just that--

112
00:08:49,067 --> 00:08:53,614
I have so much luggage,
and you're so, um, streamlined.

113
00:08:53,697 --> 00:08:56,074
It's, you know,
humiliating.

114
00:08:56,158 --> 00:08:58,076
[ Italian ]

115
00:08:58,202 --> 00:09:00,120
I'm Meredith,
by the way.

116
00:09:00,204 --> 00:09:04,750
- Hello, I'm Dickie.
- Meredith Randall.

117
00:09:04,833 --> 00:09:07,920
- Um, Dickie Greenleaf.
- Hello.

118
00:09:09,922 --> 00:09:12,925
You're not
the shipping Greenleafs.

119
00:09:13,008 --> 00:09:15,344
Oh, trying not to be.

120
00:09:15,427 --> 00:09:17,096
Trying to jump ship.

121
00:09:17,179 --> 00:09:20,682
So, uh, did they put
your cases in the wrong pile ?

122
00:09:20,766 --> 00:09:24,853
Itĺs just that, uh,
you were in the "R" stand.

123
00:09:24,937 --> 00:09:29,108
I thought
I saw you there.

124
00:09:29,191 --> 00:09:32,152
My father wants me
back in New York.

125
00:09:32,236 --> 00:09:35,030
He builds boats.
I'd rather sail them.

126
00:09:35,072 --> 00:09:37,658
So I travel
under my mother's name.

127
00:09:37,741 --> 00:09:41,120
- Which is--
- Emily.

128
00:09:41,203 --> 00:09:43,372
I'm just kidding.

129
00:09:44,706 --> 00:09:46,875
You know,
the funny thing is,

130
00:09:46,959 --> 00:09:49,461
I'm not Randall either.

131
00:09:50,629 --> 00:09:52,589
I'm Logue.

132
00:09:52,631 --> 00:09:55,676
- As in--
- As in the textile Logues.

133
00:09:55,759 --> 00:09:58,554
Trying to
shrug off the dress.

134
00:09:58,595 --> 00:10:00,722
- I travel under my mother's name too.
- Randall.

135
00:10:00,806 --> 00:10:02,766
Right.

136
00:10:02,808 --> 00:10:05,894
- So, Rome, Rome, Rome.
- Oh.

137
00:10:07,563 --> 00:10:11,316
- We're partners in disguise. Bye.
- Bye.

138
00:10:32,963 --> 00:10:35,090
[ Shouting in Italian ]

139
00:10:42,514 --> 00:10:46,351
[ Driver Singing in Italian ]

140
00:10:53,442 --> 00:10:56,904
[ Chattering in Italian ]

141
00:11:02,993 --> 00:11:05,746
[ Italian ]

142
00:11:11,293 --> 00:11:13,378
[Bus Motor Starts]

143
00:11:18,175 --> 00:11:22,054
- [Bus Drives Away]
- [Women Chattering]

144
00:11:23,972 --> 00:11:26,558
[Ripley Speaking
Italian Slowly]

145
00:11:28,352 --> 00:11:30,646
ôThe fiancÚe has
a face. ô

146
00:11:33,148 --> 00:11:35,234
[Resumes Speaking Italian]

147
00:11:48,163 --> 00:11:51,583
[ Italian Continues ]

148
00:11:54,920 --> 00:11:56,964
Bird.

149
00:12:00,551 --> 00:12:03,178
ôThis is my face. ô

150
00:12:08,100 --> 00:12:11,437
[ Italian ]

151
00:12:11,520 --> 00:12:14,273
[People Chattering in Italian]

152
00:12:36,503 --> 00:12:39,423
[Woman] So I guess you didn't
look at my new chapter.

153
00:12:39,506 --> 00:12:41,550
I will, Marge.
I promise.

154
00:12:41,633 --> 00:12:43,594
Itĺs just been too hot.

155
00:12:53,479 --> 00:12:56,064
If I make dinner at my place tonight,
maybe you could look at it then.

156
00:12:56,106 --> 00:12:58,442
Dickie Greenleaf?

157
00:12:58,525 --> 00:13:01,904
- Who's that ?
- It's Tom. Tom Ripley.

158
00:13:01,945 --> 00:13:03,822
Tom Ripley ?

159
00:13:03,906 --> 00:13:07,409
- We were at Princeton together.
- Okay.

160
00:13:07,493 --> 00:13:10,287
Did we know each other ?

161
00:13:10,370 --> 00:13:13,040
Hello.
Well, I knew you, so...

162
00:13:13,123 --> 00:13:15,084
I suppose
you must have known me.

163
00:13:16,668 --> 00:13:18,629
Princeton's like a fog.

164
00:13:18,670 --> 00:13:22,132
America's like a fog.

165
00:13:22,174 --> 00:13:25,511
This is Marge Sherwood.
Tom-- Sorry, what is it ?

166
00:13:25,594 --> 00:13:27,054
- Ripley.
- How do you do ?

167
00:13:27,137 --> 00:13:30,516
How do you do, Marge ?

168
00:13:30,599 --> 00:13:32,726
- What are you doing in Mongi ?
- Nothing.

169
00:13:32,810 --> 00:13:34,728
Nothing much.

170
00:13:34,812 --> 00:13:37,106
Just passing through.

171
00:13:37,189 --> 00:13:40,442
- Passing through ?
- Yeah.

172
00:13:40,526 --> 00:13:42,486
You're so white.

173
00:13:44,822 --> 00:13:47,407
Did you ever see a guy
so white, Marge ?

174
00:13:47,491 --> 00:13:49,451
Gray, actually.

175
00:13:49,535 --> 00:13:52,037
Itĺs just an undercoat.

176
00:13:52,121 --> 00:13:55,707
- Say again ?
- You know, a primer.

177
00:13:58,127 --> 00:13:59,962
That's funny.

178
00:14:00,045 --> 00:14:02,965
Margie likes that
'cause she's so white too.

179
00:14:03,006 --> 00:14:05,134
Yes, I do,
and you're not funny.

180
00:14:05,175 --> 00:14:07,136
You should come and have lunch
with us before you go.

181
00:14:07,177 --> 00:14:09,972
- Yes, Dickie ?
- Sure, anytime.

182
00:14:10,013 --> 00:14:12,474
Well,

183
00:14:12,516 --> 00:14:14,476
coincidence.

184
00:14:18,897 --> 00:14:21,191
I don't remember him.

185
00:14:21,275 --> 00:14:23,360
That's so funny.

186
00:14:29,408 --> 00:14:31,660
Silvana ! Hey !

187
00:14:33,162 --> 00:14:35,622
I've been looking all over for you.

188
00:14:35,664 --> 00:14:37,541
Whereĺve you been hiding ?

189
00:14:37,624 --> 00:14:40,502
Today you're looking for me. Where've
you been the rest of the week ?

190
00:14:40,586 --> 00:14:43,964
You're always working.
Come on. Get on.

191
00:14:44,006 --> 00:14:46,842
With the American girl ?

192
00:14:46,884 --> 00:14:48,844
- Hold on to me.
- I hate you.

193
00:14:48,886 --> 00:14:52,556
- Huh ?
- I hate you!

194
00:14:54,224 --> 00:14:56,185
[Marge]
Did you suddenly forget where I lived?

195
00:14:56,226 --> 00:14:58,395
I know. I'm late.
I'm a swine.

196
00:14:58,479 --> 00:15:00,397
- It's 4:00.
- I just woke up.

197
00:15:00,481 --> 00:15:02,941
- Ohh.
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

198
00:15:03,025 --> 00:15:05,694
- You just woke up.
- Fausto and I took the boat out.

199
00:15:05,778 --> 00:15:09,406
We were fishing, and then it was dawn,
and we caught absolutely nothing.

200
00:15:09,490 --> 00:15:13,660
Mmm, yes, well,
we ate everything without you.

201
00:15:13,702 --> 00:15:15,829
- We ?
- Yes.

202
00:15:15,913 --> 00:15:18,832
- Tom Ripley's here.
- Who ?

203
00:15:20,876 --> 00:15:24,129
- Tom. Hello.
- Hi.

204
00:15:24,213 --> 00:15:26,673
-Hello.
-How are you? Thought you'd disappeared.

205
00:15:26,757 --> 00:15:29,718
- We were gonna send out a search party.
- No.

206
00:15:29,760 --> 00:15:33,972
- No, still here.
- Tom was telling me about his journey.

207
00:15:34,056 --> 00:15:38,018
[Giggling] Made me laugh so hard
I almost got a nosebleed.

208
00:15:38,102 --> 00:15:41,688
- Is that good ?
- Shut up.

209
00:15:41,772 --> 00:15:44,733
I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.

210
00:15:44,775 --> 00:15:47,402
I'm despicable.
But I love you.

211
00:15:47,486 --> 00:15:50,405
- Do you love me ? Do you love me ?
- I'm intruding.

212
00:15:50,489 --> 00:15:52,991
Can you mix
a martini ?

213
00:15:55,202 --> 00:15:58,330
- Sure.
- [ Sighs ] I'll do it.

214
00:15:58,414 --> 00:16:01,333
- Ohh.
- I make a fabulous martini.

215
00:16:03,127 --> 00:16:06,088
[ Laughing ]

216
00:16:06,130 --> 00:16:09,508
Everybody should have
one talent. What's yours ?

217
00:16:09,591 --> 00:16:11,677
Forging signatures,

218
00:16:11,760 --> 00:16:14,805
telling lies, impersonating
practically anybody.

219
00:16:14,888 --> 00:16:18,976
That's three. Nobody should have
more than one talent.

220
00:16:20,102 --> 00:16:22,312
Okay,
do an impression.

221
00:16:22,396 --> 00:16:24,898
- Now ?
- Yeah.

222
00:16:24,982 --> 00:16:28,068
[ As Mr. Greenleaf]
The only talent my son has...

223
00:16:28,152 --> 00:16:30,612
is for cashing
his allowance.

224
00:16:32,781 --> 00:16:35,117
- What ?
- Oh, I like to sail.

225
00:16:35,200 --> 00:16:37,119
Believe me,
I love to sail.

226
00:16:37,161 --> 00:16:39,163
- Instead, I make boats.
- Stop !

227
00:16:39,246 --> 00:16:41,623
- Other people sail them.
- It's too much !

228
00:16:41,665 --> 00:16:43,667
You're making all the hairs
on my neck stand up.

229
00:16:43,751 --> 00:16:47,129
Oh, yes. Jazz.
Oh, jazz. Let's face it.

230
00:16:47,212 --> 00:16:50,758
Itĺs just, uh--
Itĺs just insolent noise.

231
00:16:50,841 --> 00:16:52,843
I feel like he's here.

232
00:16:52,926 --> 00:16:56,346
- Horrible, like the old bastard's here.
- Good.

233
00:16:56,430 --> 00:16:58,307
That's brilliant.

234
00:16:58,348 --> 00:17:01,059
Brilliant !
How do you know him ?

235
00:17:01,143 --> 00:17:02,936
Oh, I met him in New York.

236
00:17:02,978 --> 00:17:05,230
Marge !
Marge, this is scary.

237
00:17:05,314 --> 00:17:07,608
You've got to hear this.
Meet my father,

238
00:17:07,649 --> 00:17:09,860
Herbert Richard Greenleaf l.

239
00:17:09,943 --> 00:17:13,822
Pleasure to meet you.
Dickie's made a fine catch.

240
00:17:13,906 --> 00:17:16,450
- Uncanny !
- I know Emily thinks so.

241
00:17:16,492 --> 00:17:18,786
- I don't get it.
- It's uncanny.

242
00:17:18,827 --> 00:17:21,955
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy, Tom,

243
00:17:22,039 --> 00:17:25,000
and, uh, bringing him back ?

244
00:17:25,042 --> 00:17:27,252
- What ?
- I'd pay you.

245
00:17:27,336 --> 00:17:29,254
If you would go
to Italy,

246
00:17:29,338 --> 00:17:33,300
persuade my son to come home,
I'd pay you a thousand dollars.

247
00:17:35,969 --> 00:17:37,971
[Dickie]
Iĺm never going back.

248
00:17:38,013 --> 00:17:40,724
To actually hire somebody
to come all the way here...

249
00:17:40,808 --> 00:17:42,726
to drag me back home--

250
00:17:42,810 --> 00:17:44,937
Got to be a little
insane, doesn't he ?

251
00:17:45,020 --> 00:17:47,523
- Ciao, Fausto.
- [ Italian ]

252
00:17:51,527 --> 00:17:54,029
- This is Tom.
- Ciao, Tom.

253
00:17:54,071 --> 00:17:56,198
[ Italian ]

254
00:17:56,281 --> 00:17:58,826
- I'm never going back.
- No, I think--

255
00:17:58,867 --> 00:18:00,869
Your mother, her illness,
I think that's--

256
00:18:00,911 --> 00:18:03,997
It's got nothing to do
with my mother.

257
00:18:04,081 --> 00:18:07,751
She's had leukem--
This is what makes me boil about him.

258
00:18:07,835 --> 00:18:11,422
He wants me back.
He wants me back.

259
00:18:11,505 --> 00:18:13,882
- It's got nothing to do with my mother.
- Look, I don't know--

260
00:18:13,924 --> 00:18:15,884
Go back.
Go back to New York.

261
00:18:15,926 --> 00:18:18,011
Or call him, if you can find
a telephone that works,

262
00:18:18,053 --> 00:18:22,558
and tell him wild horses wouldn't
drag me back to him or his shipyard.

263
00:18:25,018 --> 00:18:28,021
- Hi, Tom.
- Hi.

264
00:18:28,105 --> 00:18:30,399
Marge, Tom's saying good-bye.

265
00:18:30,482 --> 00:18:32,526
Oh, I'll come down.

266
00:18:34,027 --> 00:18:36,447
So, uh, did you
speak to my father ?

267
00:18:36,530 --> 00:18:38,740
Oh, you were right...
about the telephones.

268
00:18:38,824 --> 00:18:40,743
- I told you.
- There are no lines.

269
00:18:40,826 --> 00:18:43,579
- There's some problem.
- That's Italy.

270
00:18:45,289 --> 00:18:49,418
Tom. You're off ?
What are your plans ?

271
00:18:49,501 --> 00:18:51,920
Oh, back, I suppose,
as slow as I can. Oh !

272
00:18:52,713 --> 00:18:55,674
This bag !

273
00:18:57,092 --> 00:19:00,262
Hey.
You like jazz.

274
00:19:00,345 --> 00:19:02,014
I love jazz.

275
00:19:04,558 --> 00:19:06,518
This is the best.

276
00:19:06,560 --> 00:19:09,688
Baker, Rollins.

277
00:19:09,730 --> 00:19:12,941
Marge says she likes jazz,
but she thinks Glenn Millerĺs jazz.

278
00:19:13,025 --> 00:19:14,985
- I never said that !
- [Tom] Bird.

279
00:19:15,068 --> 00:19:17,321
Thatĺs jazz.

280
00:19:17,404 --> 00:19:19,698
Bird ? Ask me
the name of my sailboat.

281
00:19:19,740 --> 00:19:21,742
I don't know. What's the name
of your sailboat ?

282
00:19:21,784 --> 00:19:23,994
Look ! Look !
Bird !

283
00:19:24,078 --> 00:19:26,789
[Marge]
Which is ridiculous. Boats are female.

284
00:19:26,872 --> 00:19:30,250
Everyone knows you can't
call a boat after a man.

285
00:19:30,292 --> 00:19:33,462
- He's not a man. He's a god.
- Okay, we're going to Naples.

286
00:19:33,545 --> 00:19:36,131
There's a club--
It's not a club, it's a cellar.

287
00:19:36,215 --> 00:19:39,134
-It's vile.
-Yes, it's vile. You don't have to come.

288
00:19:39,218 --> 00:19:41,845
It's great. It's-- It's great.
You're gonna love it.

289
00:20:12,876 --> 00:20:16,171
How are you ?

290
00:20:16,255 --> 00:20:18,257
-[Ends]
- [People Applauding]

291
00:20:18,340 --> 00:20:20,217
Oh !

292
00:20:20,300 --> 00:20:22,177
[ Italian ]

293
00:20:58,422 --> 00:21:00,048
That'd be cool.
Bring him up.

294
00:21:00,132 --> 00:21:02,134
[ Italian ]

295
00:21:04,219 --> 00:21:06,305
Tom Ripley !

296
00:21:08,474 --> 00:21:10,809
Come on !
Get on up here !

297
00:21:12,686 --> 00:21:15,647
- Yeah !
-  [ Italian ]

298
00:21:16,774 --> 00:21:18,817
I'll tell you when
to join the chorus.

299
00:21:18,901 --> 00:21:20,861
Come on.

300
00:21:29,912 --> 00:21:32,247
Okay.
Together !

301
00:21:32,331 --> 00:21:36,502
[ Italian ]

302
00:22:12,079 --> 00:22:13,622
[Dickie] I bumped into
an old friend from Princeton,

303
00:22:13,705 --> 00:22:16,208
- a fellow called Tom Ripley.
- [Keyboard Clacking]

304
00:22:16,291 --> 00:22:20,045
He says he's going to haunt me
until I agree...

305
00:22:20,087 --> 00:22:24,466
to go back to New York...

306
00:22:24,550 --> 00:22:26,969
with him.

307
00:22:31,432 --> 00:22:34,059
Afternoon.

308
00:22:34,101 --> 00:22:36,103
What time is it ?

309
00:22:36,145 --> 00:22:38,105
- Oh, God.
- ôGo back to New York with him. ô

310
00:22:39,440 --> 00:22:42,234
- Here--
- You always type your letters ?

311
00:22:44,111 --> 00:22:47,573
- That should be two T's.
- I can't write, and I can't spell.

312
00:22:47,656 --> 00:22:50,576
It's the privilege
of a first-class education.

313
00:22:50,617 --> 00:22:52,703
Your room's
upstairs at the back.

314
00:22:52,786 --> 00:22:55,414
I think Ermalinda
made up the bed. Ermalinda !

315
00:22:55,497 --> 00:22:58,000
[ Both Speaking Italian ]

316
00:22:58,083 --> 00:23:01,044
- This is so good of you.
- Don't say it again.

317
00:23:04,923 --> 00:23:08,093
Now that you're a double agent
and we're going to string my dad along,

318
00:23:08,135 --> 00:23:10,929
what if we were to buy
a car with your expense money ?

319
00:23:10,971 --> 00:23:13,265
- Okay.
- Great.

320
00:23:13,307 --> 00:23:15,434
- Hello, Tom.
- Hello.

321
00:23:15,517 --> 00:23:17,811
Marge, Marge,
what do you think ?

322
00:23:17,895 --> 00:23:20,063
Little Ciquencento
with my dad's money ?

323
00:23:20,147 --> 00:23:22,983
Oh, please, Dickie.
You can't even drive a car.

324
00:23:23,066 --> 00:23:26,403
- [Tom] You can't even drive.
- What we need urgently is an icebox.

325
00:23:26,487 --> 00:23:29,198
What do you think ? Agree with me,
and I'll be your friend for life.

326
00:23:30,324 --> 00:23:33,911
- I absolutely agree with Marge.
- Hmm.

327
00:23:33,994 --> 00:23:36,413
Icebox. Icebox.

328
00:23:40,250 --> 00:23:42,461
[Bell Tolling]

329
00:23:48,675 --> 00:23:50,803
[Marge]
So, what, is he gonna move in with you ?

330
00:23:50,886 --> 00:23:55,557
It'll just be for a little while.
He can be-- He makes me laugh.

331
00:23:55,641 --> 00:23:59,144
- Okay, darling.
- Promise you'd say ?

332
00:23:59,228 --> 00:24:03,065
- No, I like him.
- Marge, you like everybody.

333
00:24:03,148 --> 00:24:05,859
Don't like you.
[Chuckles]

334
00:24:05,943 --> 00:24:08,445
Then I'll go to your place
and you can move in with Tom.

335
00:24:17,788 --> 00:24:19,706
[ Imitating Marge ]
I like him.

336
00:24:19,790 --> 00:24:23,460
[ Imitating Dickie ]
Marge, you like everybody.

337
00:24:27,714 --> 00:24:30,634
[ Imitating Marge ]
No, I like him.

338
00:24:30,717 --> 00:24:35,556
[ Imitating Dickie ]
Marge, you like everybody.

339
00:24:35,639 --> 00:24:39,143
[Dickie] Now you'll find out why Miss
Sherwood always shows up for breakfast.

340
00:24:39,226 --> 00:24:41,854
It's not love.
It's my coffee machine.

341
00:24:41,895 --> 00:24:44,648
[Marge] Ever since Ermalinda
showed him how to make his own espresso,

342
00:24:44,731 --> 00:24:46,984
he feels like quite
the grownup.

343
00:24:47,025 --> 00:24:49,820
-I bought the coffee machine.
-[Marge] Oh, darling, is that for me ?

344
00:24:49,903 --> 00:24:52,197
This is for Tom,
because he didn't complain.

345
00:24:52,281 --> 00:24:55,117
[Tom]
That ring is superb.

346
00:24:55,200 --> 00:24:57,661
Oh, Tom, I love you.
See ?

347
00:24:57,745 --> 00:25:02,750
Ooh ! I had to promise,
capital "P," never to take it off.

348
00:25:02,833 --> 00:25:06,170
-Otherwise, I'd give it to you.
-Isn't it great ? I found it in Naples.

349
00:25:06,211 --> 00:25:08,797
I had to bargain for it
for about two weeks.

350
00:25:08,881 --> 00:25:11,300
I hope it wasn't cheap,
Marge.

351
00:25:11,383 --> 00:25:14,303
- Oh, it was.
- [ Chuckles ]

352
00:25:14,386 --> 00:25:17,973
I have to get a birthday present for
Frances, so perhaps you could help me.

353
00:25:18,056 --> 00:25:20,893
- Who's Frances ?
- My fiancÚe.

354
00:25:20,934 --> 00:25:23,771
Engaged ?
You're a dark horse, Ripley.

355
00:25:23,854 --> 00:25:25,773
- Who is she ?
- Your parents met her.

356
00:25:25,856 --> 00:25:29,735
Oh, God.
Oh, I can just imagine.

357
00:25:29,818 --> 00:25:32,029
"If only Dickie
would settle down.

358
00:25:32,070 --> 00:25:34,156
Doesn't every parent
deserve a grandchild ?"

359
00:25:34,239 --> 00:25:37,076
Oh, God.
Never. Never.

360
00:25:37,117 --> 00:25:41,705
I swear on your ring, Marge,
I'm never going back.

361
00:25:41,789 --> 00:25:44,291
- [ Tom ] Say when to pull.
- [ Dickie ] Pull now. Pull.

362
00:25:44,374 --> 00:25:48,212
It's not pulling.
I'm doing it wrong.

363
00:25:50,047 --> 00:25:52,382
- Better now, huh ?
- Okay, okay, okay.

364
00:25:52,466 --> 00:25:54,384
We'll make a sailor
of you yet.

365
00:25:54,468 --> 00:25:56,804
You're doing really well.

366
00:25:56,887 --> 00:26:00,099
- All right. Bar's open.
- Yes, please.

367
00:26:00,182 --> 00:26:03,310
- Hey, can we sail to Venice ?
- Sure. I love Venice.

368
00:26:05,437 --> 00:26:08,107
"See Venice and die."
Isn't that right ? Or is it Rome ?

369
00:26:08,148 --> 00:26:11,235
- Is it Rome ?
- I have to see Venice.

370
00:26:11,318 --> 00:26:15,155
You do something and die, don't you ?
Okay. Venice is on the list.

371
00:26:15,239 --> 00:26:17,783
And Rome.

372
00:26:17,866 --> 00:26:19,910
Do you ski ?

373
00:26:22,162 --> 00:26:24,915
Ah, no, no.
Don't tell me.

374
00:26:24,998 --> 00:26:28,252
You're a lost cause.
That's the next thing to deal with.

375
00:26:28,293 --> 00:26:30,963
Christmas, weĺre planning
a skiing trip to Cortina.

376
00:26:31,004 --> 00:26:34,425
- Excellent skiing. Excellent. Marge.
- Yes ?

377
00:26:34,508 --> 00:26:37,177
Unbelievable.
Tom can't ski either.

378
00:26:37,261 --> 00:26:40,431
- We'll have to teach him that too.
- Thank you.

379
00:26:42,516 --> 00:26:45,727
Such low class, Marge.
Does this guy know anything ?

380
00:26:45,811 --> 00:26:48,063
Good thing we're not
getting married soon.

381
00:26:48,147 --> 00:26:50,858
We'd have to invite Tom
on our honeymoon.

382
00:26:54,153 --> 00:26:57,072
[Marge] Oh, I hated New York.
That whole Park Avenue crowd.

383
00:26:57,156 --> 00:26:59,116
So I fled to Paris
to work on my book.

384
00:26:59,199 --> 00:27:02,286
And I was always going
to this cafe in Monmartre...

385
00:27:02,369 --> 00:27:04,329
with Jean-Jaques.

386
00:27:04,371 --> 00:27:07,958
And Dickie would play
"My Funny Valentine."

387
00:27:08,041 --> 00:27:13,338
It was only later that I found out
he only knows about six songs.

388
00:27:13,422 --> 00:27:15,758
Anyway, I looked forward
to seeing him, I suppose.

389
00:27:15,841 --> 00:27:19,136
[ Speaking Italian ]

390
00:27:37,070 --> 00:27:39,406
[Men Chattering in Italian]

391
00:27:42,159 --> 00:27:45,871
Hey, hey, Signor Greenleaf !

392
00:27:45,913 --> 00:27:49,583
You're not at my place by 7.:00,
Tom and I are running off together.

393
00:27:49,666 --> 00:27:52,461
- Okay, fine.
- [Man] Oh, Dickie !

394
00:27:56,006 --> 00:27:58,592
[ Indistinct ]

395
00:28:02,763 --> 00:28:05,307
Oh, hold on.
Hold on.

396
00:28:05,390 --> 00:28:09,645
Silvana, Silvana

397
00:28:09,728 --> 00:28:11,647
You make me smile

398
00:28:11,730 --> 00:28:14,858
I need
to talk to you.

399
00:28:14,942 --> 00:28:17,861
[Continues]

400
00:28:20,906 --> 00:28:24,118
- [ Dickie ] You're breaking my ribs !
- What ?

401
00:28:25,661 --> 00:28:28,497
You're breaking my ribs !

402
00:28:30,290 --> 00:28:33,502
But don't

403
00:28:33,585 --> 00:28:37,214
Change a hair for me

404
00:28:40,008 --> 00:28:42,052
Not if you care

405
00:28:42,136 --> 00:28:44,430
For me

406
00:28:46,598 --> 00:28:51,270
Stay, little Valentine

407
00:28:52,646 --> 00:28:56,108
Stay

408
00:29:00,487 --> 00:29:02,448
Each day

409
00:29:02,531 --> 00:29:09,913
Is Valentine's Day

410
00:29:13,542 --> 00:29:15,127
Ohh !
[ Kisses ]

411
00:29:15,210 --> 00:29:20,174
I could fuck this icebox,
I love it so much.

412
00:29:21,925 --> 00:29:25,471
So, what did you actually
do in New York ?

413
00:29:25,554 --> 00:29:28,307
Played piano in a few places.
I told you.

414
00:29:28,390 --> 00:29:31,435
Well, that's one job.
You told me a lot of jobs.

415
00:29:31,518 --> 00:29:34,021
Few places.
That's a few jobs.

416
00:29:34,062 --> 00:29:36,148
The mysterious Mr. Ripley.

417
00:29:36,231 --> 00:29:39,067
Marge and I spend
hours speculating.

418
00:29:39,151 --> 00:29:42,404
Anyway, I don't even want
to think about New York.

419
00:29:42,488 --> 00:29:45,032
Are you ready ?

420
00:29:45,074 --> 00:29:49,286
- Cold beer. Thank you, Dad.
- Okay.

421
00:29:49,369 --> 00:29:51,455
Copy out from here.

422
00:29:53,082 --> 00:29:56,418
- You bring this with you to Europe ?
- You gonna write something ?

423
00:29:56,460 --> 00:29:59,713
I love the fact that you brought
Shakespeare with you but no clothes.

424
00:29:59,755 --> 00:30:03,175
Ermalinda says you wash out the same
shirt every night. Is that true ?

425
00:30:03,258 --> 00:30:05,177
No. I have more
than one shirt.

426
00:30:05,260 --> 00:30:07,429
She can do that for you.

427
00:30:07,513 --> 00:30:10,140
Anyway, just wear
some of my stuff.

428
00:30:10,224 --> 00:30:12,643
Wear anything you want.
Most of it's ancient.

429
00:30:14,853 --> 00:30:16,939
Now your signature.

430
00:30:19,775 --> 00:30:22,778
Not Dickie.
Your signature.

431
00:30:33,622 --> 00:30:35,749
Without the glasses,
you're not even ugly.

432
00:30:38,127 --> 00:30:41,130
I don't need them
because I never read.

433
00:30:42,297 --> 00:30:45,008
- How do I look ?
- Like Clark Kent.

434
00:30:47,636 --> 00:30:50,848
- Now Superman.
- Superman.

435
00:30:55,477 --> 00:30:57,938
- Okay.
- I know.

436
00:30:57,980 --> 00:31:02,818
It's like a kid's. See this, the ôSö
and the ôTö ? Fine, vulnerable.

437
00:31:02,901 --> 00:31:05,946
That's pain.
That's secret pain.

438
00:31:05,988 --> 00:31:08,907
Well, that must be a very deep secret,
'cause I don't know about it.

439
00:31:08,991 --> 00:31:12,286
Hmm. There's nothing more
naked than your handwriting.

440
00:31:12,327 --> 00:31:15,080
See how nothing's
quite touching the line ?

441
00:31:15,164 --> 00:31:18,625
- That's vanity.
- Well, we certainly know that's true.

442
00:31:24,339 --> 00:31:27,301
[ Dickie ]
Do you have any brothers ?

443
00:31:27,384 --> 00:31:30,345
No.

444
00:31:30,387 --> 00:31:32,514
No brothers,
no sisters.

445
00:31:34,767 --> 00:31:37,227
Me neither.

446
00:31:37,311 --> 00:31:39,480
Nor does Marge.

447
00:31:41,106 --> 00:31:43,859
All only children.

448
00:31:49,865 --> 00:31:51,992
What does that mean ?

449
00:31:54,203 --> 00:31:56,663
Means we've never
shared a bath.

450
00:32:00,626 --> 00:32:03,545
And I'm cold.
Can I get in ?

451
00:32:08,801 --> 00:32:11,470
No.

452
00:32:14,681 --> 00:32:17,392
I didn't mean
with you in it.

453
00:32:21,230 --> 00:32:24,858
Okay.

454
00:32:24,900 --> 00:32:28,529
Get in. I'm like
a prune anyway.

455
00:32:50,259 --> 00:32:52,344
It is me.
It's an old picture.

456
00:32:52,428 --> 00:32:56,432
Every time ! "Is it you ?
It doesn't look like you."

457
00:32:56,515 --> 00:32:58,392
God !

458
00:32:58,434 --> 00:33:01,270
Letters-- Greenleaf
and for Ripley.

459
00:33:01,311 --> 00:33:04,273
Ooh. Fran. "I miss you.
When are you coming home ?

460
00:33:04,314 --> 00:33:06,900
Stop telling me what
an incredible time you're having.

461
00:33:06,942 --> 00:33:09,069
- How much you love Dickie.
- Whoo !

462
00:33:09,111 --> 00:33:12,239
And Marge
and Mongibello."

463
00:33:12,322 --> 00:33:14,324
And this one, I think,
is from your father.

464
00:33:14,408 --> 00:33:18,078
[Dickie Vocalizing: Jazz]

465
00:33:18,120 --> 00:33:23,167
- Let me see it. What does he say ?
- He's getting impatient.

466
00:33:23,250 --> 00:33:27,671
He wants me to reassure him that you're
going to be home by Thanksgiving.

467
00:33:27,755 --> 00:33:30,591
You've got to get
a new jacket. Really.

468
00:33:30,632 --> 00:33:32,843
You must be sick
of wearing the same clothes.

469
00:33:32,926 --> 00:33:35,888
I can't. I can't keep spending
your father's money.

470
00:33:35,971 --> 00:33:38,891
I love how
responsible you are.

471
00:33:38,974 --> 00:33:42,102
My dad should make you
chief accountant or something.

472
00:33:42,144 --> 00:33:45,147
Or when I take over,
which is never, I will.

473
00:33:45,189 --> 00:33:48,901
Okay. When you take over,
which is never, I'll accept.

474
00:33:48,984 --> 00:33:51,111
Let me buy you a jacket. When we
get to Rome, there's a great place--

475
00:33:51,195 --> 00:33:54,823
- Battistoni.
- Battistoni.

476
00:33:54,907 --> 00:33:58,577
[ Italian ]

477
00:33:58,660 --> 00:34:01,830
Roma, we're taking Tom
to Roma

478
00:34:01,872 --> 00:34:05,292
Weĺre going to a-Roma

479
00:34:05,334 --> 00:34:08,295
[ Chattering in Italian ]

480
00:34:13,050 --> 00:34:15,844
Buongiorno.
Nice sweater.

481
00:34:15,928 --> 00:34:17,971
Where do we get
a carrozza for the Forum ?

482
00:34:18,055 --> 00:34:20,307
- Can we just hire any of them ?
- Relax.

483
00:34:20,349 --> 00:34:23,018
Relax !

484
00:34:23,102 --> 00:34:25,896
Itĺs just there's so much
to do in a single day.

485
00:34:25,979 --> 00:34:29,942
The most important question is where to
eat. I hope Freddie made a reservation.

486
00:34:30,025 --> 00:34:31,944
Freddie ?

487
00:34:32,027 --> 00:34:35,322
Freddie.
Freddie Miles.

488
00:34:35,364 --> 00:34:37,699
Freddie's organizing
the Cortina skiing trip.

489
00:34:37,783 --> 00:34:39,535
Oh.

490
00:34:39,576 --> 00:34:42,162
Oh, here he is.

