you know, in the daylight,

972
01:15:06,295 --> 01:15:08,422
so it's not just this.

973
01:15:08,505 --> 01:15:11,258
Of course. Meredith, I'm sorry.
Of course I'll meet you.

974
01:15:11,341 --> 01:15:16,597
You should always
save pain for daylight.

975
01:15:16,638 --> 01:15:19,933
Why don't we have coffee
in the morning at Dinelli's ?

976
01:15:20,017 --> 01:15:22,186
Uh, by the Spanish Steps.

977
01:15:22,269 --> 01:15:24,104
Exactly. 1 0:30 ?

978
01:15:26,815 --> 01:15:29,443
- 1 0:1 5.
- Okay.

979
01:15:29,485 --> 01:15:31,653
Okay.

980
01:15:40,120 --> 01:15:44,041
[Bell Tolling]

981
01:15:46,877 --> 01:15:48,754
[Tolling Continues]

982
01:15:58,847 --> 01:16:00,808
[ Italian ]

983
01:16:17,324 --> 01:16:20,786
[ Chattering, indistinct ]

984
01:16:22,871 --> 01:16:25,207
- [ Peter ] Grazie.
- Peter ?

985
01:16:25,290 --> 01:16:28,794
Hello.
It's Meredith Logue.

986
01:16:28,877 --> 01:16:31,547
[Peter] Of course it is.
Meredith, hello. Sorry.

987
01:16:31,630 --> 01:16:34,675
- I was half asleep. How are you ?
- How are you ?

988
01:16:34,758 --> 01:16:37,136
This is Marge Sherwood.
Meredith Logue.

989
01:16:37,177 --> 01:16:40,222
How do you do ?

990
01:16:40,305 --> 01:16:43,642
Do join us, wonĺt you ?
Weĺre just waiting for a friend.

991
01:16:43,684 --> 01:16:46,437
I-- I won't, actually.
I think there's--

992
01:16:46,520 --> 01:16:49,106
- Did we see you at the opera last night ?
- Uh--

993
01:16:49,189 --> 01:16:51,900
Are you waiting for Dickie ?

994
01:16:51,984 --> 01:16:56,113
Dickie ? Do you-- Do you--
Do you know Dickie ?

995
01:16:56,196 --> 01:16:59,324
You were at the opera.
Oh, that explains-- Yes, I was there.

996
01:16:59,408 --> 01:17:02,953
I was there with Dickie.

997
01:17:04,037 --> 01:17:06,790
[ Exhales ]
I knew it.

998
01:17:06,874 --> 01:17:09,084
I told you.

999
01:17:11,170 --> 01:17:15,674
Marge, I don't know you,
so I've got no right to--

1000
01:17:15,758 --> 01:17:18,969
Dickie loves you.
He's-- Well--

1001
01:17:19,053 --> 01:17:22,181
I think youĺll find
he's on his way home to you.

1002
01:17:22,264 --> 01:17:26,310
[ Sighs ] Well, how-how-how
would you know that ?

1003
01:17:27,561 --> 01:17:30,105
He... told me everything.

1004
01:17:30,189 --> 01:17:35,110
No, I was supposed to meet him
1 5 minutes ago, so, uh,

1005
01:17:35,194 --> 01:17:37,613
I'm gonna go now,
I think.

1006
01:17:39,907 --> 01:17:41,992
God, unless he meant us
to meet.

1007
01:17:42,076 --> 01:17:44,244
Thatĺd be a little cruel,
wouldn't it ?

1008
01:17:44,328 --> 01:17:46,747
No, no, we're
meeting another friend.

1009
01:17:46,789 --> 01:17:49,625
- Tom Ripley.
- Do you know Tom Ripley ?

1010
01:17:49,708 --> 01:17:54,546
No, no. I've heard about him,
of course, but I didn't meet him, no.

1011
01:17:54,588 --> 01:17:57,091
- [Italian]
- Not for me. No, grazie.

1012
01:18:02,429 --> 01:18:05,349
Hope I didn't
complicate matters.

1013
01:18:05,432 --> 01:18:10,771
God, nothing, nothing...
untoward happened.

1014
01:18:10,813 --> 01:18:15,067
No, there is nothing to prevent you
from welcoming him back,

1015
01:18:15,109 --> 01:18:17,069
from marrying him.

1016
01:18:21,615 --> 01:18:24,326
Good-bye.
I'm happy to put a face to a name.

1017
01:18:24,410 --> 01:18:26,912
Good-bye, Peter.
Please, don't get up.

1018
01:18:47,433 --> 01:18:50,561
[ Marge ] Now I don't know what to
think. Do you think he's coming back ?

1019
01:18:52,146 --> 01:18:55,566
Sorry. Sorry.
Had to renew my papers.

1020
01:18:55,649 --> 01:18:57,985
Never one stamp when they
can make you line up for three.

1021
01:18:58,026 --> 01:19:00,154
- Have you been waiting long ?
- Not at all.

1022
01:19:00,237 --> 01:19:02,948
- Morning, Tom.
- Hi. Sorry.

1023
01:19:03,031 --> 01:19:04,992
You okay ? You look like
youĺve seen a ghost.

1024
01:19:05,033 --> 01:19:07,745
Dickie was at the opera
last night.

1025
01:19:07,828 --> 01:19:11,165
I don't believe that. Uh--
Wild horses couldn't drag Dickie--

1026
01:19:11,206 --> 01:19:13,500
[ Laughs ] Well, he was there
with someone, you know,

1027
01:19:13,584 --> 01:19:16,086
so I suppose she must
have dragged him.

1028
01:19:16,170 --> 01:19:19,006
It's not fair.

1029
01:19:19,047 --> 01:19:23,218
I think I'm going back to Mongi.
I think Dickie's coming home.

1030
01:19:23,302 --> 01:19:25,929
Really ? l-- Well,
thatĺs just swell.

1031
01:19:26,013 --> 01:19:28,640
No, you know, you're
way ahead of me. Great.

1032
01:19:28,724 --> 01:19:30,684
That was rather moving
when I heard-- I'm sorry.

1033
01:19:30,768 --> 01:19:33,187
Meredith is the American girl
I saw at the opera last night.

1034
01:19:33,228 --> 01:19:37,316
- Sheĺs been seeing something of Dickie.
- Oh, my God.

1035
01:19:37,399 --> 01:19:40,861
But the point is,
Dickie-- and we all know this.

1036
01:19:40,944 --> 01:19:44,615
Dickie loves Marge.
And he misses her.

1037
01:19:44,698 --> 01:19:47,451
I feel guilty.
Marge doesn't understand this,

1038
01:19:47,534 --> 01:19:50,370
but whenever Dickie does
something, I feel guilty.

1039
01:19:50,454 --> 01:19:52,748
[ Chuckles ]
As if that makes sense.

1040
01:19:54,541 --> 01:19:57,878
[ Italian ]

1041
01:19:57,961 --> 01:20:00,005
[ Italian ]

1042
01:20:19,233 --> 01:20:22,152
[Choir Singing
in Italian]

1043
01:20:46,176 --> 01:20:48,095
[Ends]

1044
01:20:58,021 --> 01:20:59,940
[Knocking At Door]

1045
01:21:08,615 --> 01:21:11,660
- [Knocking]
- [Piano: Stops]

1046
01:21:16,165 --> 01:21:18,125
[Freddie]
Dickie.

1047
01:21:19,793 --> 01:21:22,171
- [Knocking]
- Dickie, come on. It's me.

1048
01:21:24,631 --> 01:21:26,550
It's Freddie.
Let me in.

1049
01:21:29,595 --> 01:21:31,513
Dickie.

1050
01:21:36,810 --> 01:21:39,605
Hello, Freddie.
It's Tom.

1051
01:21:40,689 --> 01:21:43,650
Um, where's Dickie ?

1052
01:21:43,692 --> 01:21:45,652
How are you ?

1053
01:21:45,694 --> 01:21:48,781
I'm good. Uh, yes, thank you.
He's gone. He went to dinner.

1054
01:21:48,822 --> 01:21:53,202
- He's at Otello's. You know Otello's ?
- No, no, no.

1055
01:21:53,285 --> 01:21:56,080
I-l don't think he's
at dinner at 6:30 P.M.

1056
01:21:56,163 --> 01:21:59,458
If you said he was still at lunch,
maybe I'd believe you.

1057
01:21:59,500 --> 01:22:03,128
You know ? [ Laughs ]
Incredible.

1058
01:22:03,170 --> 01:22:07,132
I mean, the guy just, you know,
disappeared off the face of the earth.

1059
01:22:09,301 --> 01:22:11,220
I guess.

1060
01:22:12,346 --> 01:22:15,432
The landlady,
as far as I could tell--

1061
01:22:15,516 --> 01:22:19,311
The landlady said
he was here right now.

1062
01:22:19,353 --> 01:22:21,605
Search the place.

1063
01:22:21,688 --> 01:22:25,067
I-l just don't-- I don't know why you'd
imagine that Dickie would hide from you.

1064
01:22:25,150 --> 01:22:27,069
Because he's been
hiding from me.

1065
01:22:29,238 --> 01:22:33,075
- What happened at Christmas ?
- What about Christmas ?

1066
01:22:33,158 --> 01:22:36,286
He was supposed to come skiing.
I didn't get a cable...

1067
01:22:36,370 --> 01:22:38,580
or a call or a little note
or a--

1068
01:22:38,664 --> 01:22:43,168
- [ Grunts ]
- Frankly, a fart.

1069
01:22:43,252 --> 01:22:45,504
Well, he's been very involved
with his music.

1070
01:22:45,587 --> 01:22:49,800
Um, I think his theory... is...

1071
01:22:49,883 --> 01:22:54,471
that you have to go into a cocoon,
uh, before you can be a butterfly.

1072
01:22:54,555 --> 01:22:57,099
Which is horseshit.
[ Mutters ]

1073
01:22:57,182 --> 01:23:00,644
You hear him play this thing ?
Well, he can't.

1074
01:23:03,522 --> 01:23:05,607
How did you find him ?

1075
01:23:05,691 --> 01:23:08,694
It's such an out-of-the-way apartment.
Can I fixyou a drink ?

1076
01:23:08,736 --> 01:23:11,739
No, thanks.
At the American Express.

1077
01:23:11,780 --> 01:23:15,075
[ Strikes Random Keys ]

1078
01:23:15,159 --> 01:23:17,578
Some kid.
[ Strikes Keys ]

1079
01:23:23,083 --> 01:23:26,044
Are you living here ?

1080
01:23:26,086 --> 01:23:29,214
No, no. I'm staying here
for a few days.

1081
01:23:31,884 --> 01:23:34,553
- But--
- [Strikes Keys]

1082
01:23:34,595 --> 01:23:38,307
It's a new piano.
Probably shouldn't--

1083
01:23:38,390 --> 01:23:41,685
[ Striking Keys ]

1084
01:23:42,853 --> 01:23:45,439
- Probably shouldn't--
- [Strikes Keys]

1085
01:23:48,400 --> 01:23:52,154
Did this place come furnished ?

1086
01:23:52,237 --> 01:23:55,407
It doesn't
look like Dickie's, uh--

1087
01:23:55,491 --> 01:23:58,577
It's really horrible,
isn't it ?

1088
01:24:00,162 --> 01:24:03,665
It's so, uh, bourgeois.

1089
01:24:13,175 --> 01:24:15,386
Oh, that's a, uh--
You should-- Watch that.

1090
01:24:15,469 --> 01:24:18,597
Excuse--
Excuse me.

1091
01:24:18,639 --> 01:24:20,599
Excuse me.

1092
01:24:23,602 --> 01:24:28,273
In fact, the only thing that looks
like Dickie... is you.

1093
01:24:28,315 --> 01:24:30,359
- Hardly.
- Hmm.

1094
01:24:32,319 --> 01:24:35,030
Have you done something
to your hair ?

1095
01:24:35,114 --> 01:24:37,116
Is there something
you'd like to say, Freddie ?

1096
01:24:37,199 --> 01:24:39,618
- What ?
- You have something you'd like to say ?

1097
01:24:39,660 --> 01:24:42,037
I think I'm saying it.

1098
01:24:43,497 --> 01:24:46,625
Somethingĺs going on.

1099
01:24:46,708 --> 01:24:49,545
Either he's converted
to Christianity,

1100
01:24:50,754 --> 01:24:52,673
or there's something else.

1101
01:24:54,133 --> 01:24:56,260
Well, I would suggest you
ask Dickie that yourself.

1102
01:24:56,343 --> 01:24:59,221
Otello's is on della Croce
just off the Corso.

1103
01:24:59,304 --> 01:25:02,766
Is it on della Croce
just off the Corso ?

1104
01:25:04,852 --> 01:25:09,106
Sure. You're
a quick study, arenĺt you ?

1105
01:25:09,189 --> 01:25:11,108
Last time you didn't know
you ass from your elbow.

1106
01:25:11,191 --> 01:25:13,610
Now you're giving me directions.

1107
01:25:13,694 --> 01:25:17,448
Thatĺs not fair. You probably
do know your ass from your elbow.

1108
01:25:20,367 --> 01:25:22,286
I'll see you.

1109
01:25:26,874 --> 01:25:29,293
[Door Opens, Closes]

1110
01:25:31,754 --> 01:25:34,339
[ Italian ]

1111
01:25:34,423 --> 01:25:37,009
[Freddie]
No Dickie Greenleaf. Thomas Ripley.

1112
01:25:37,092 --> 01:25:40,512
Si.
[Italian]

1113
01:25:45,726 --> 01:25:47,686
Ciao, Dickie.

1114
01:25:52,191 --> 01:25:54,651
Dickie doesn't
play the piano.

1115
01:25:56,195 --> 01:25:58,113
[Freddie]
Tommy.

1116
01:25:58,197 --> 01:26:00,115
Tommy!

1117
01:26:00,199 --> 01:26:02,117
Tommy!

1118
01:26:03,911 --> 01:26:06,914
[Freddie Groaning]

1119
01:26:24,973 --> 01:26:27,935
[Tom Grunting]

1120
01:26:35,859 --> 01:26:39,488
[Man And Woman Chattering]

1121
01:26:40,656 --> 01:26:43,450
Oh ! [ Laughs ]
You're making me laugh.

1122
01:26:43,534 --> 01:26:47,329
No. Youĺre just so drunk.
Oh. Youĺre just--

1123
01:26:47,413 --> 01:26:50,749
What can you do, eh ?
You should see my other friends.

1124
01:26:50,791 --> 01:26:53,210
- What canyon do ?
- [ Italian ]

1125
01:26:53,293 --> 01:26:56,505
Yes.
Such a pig.

1126
01:26:58,006 --> 01:26:59,967
- [ Laughs ]
- [ Italian ]

1127
01:27:00,008 --> 01:27:05,264
[ Imitating Freddie ] Hey, if I'm drunk,
think what her husband's saying.

1128
01:27:52,686 --> 01:27:55,064
- La polizia.
- Dickie Greenleaf?

1129
01:27:55,147 --> 01:27:58,150
- Yes.
- Inspector Roverini.

1130
01:27:58,233 --> 01:28:00,235
- Can we come in ?
- Please.

1131
01:28:07,993 --> 01:28:10,287
It's a terrible shock,
huh ?

1132
01:28:10,370 --> 01:28:14,083
W-What time did Signor Miles
leave yesterday ?

1133
01:28:14,166 --> 01:28:18,170
Oh, um, I can't be certain
exactly. I--

1134
01:28:18,253 --> 01:28:20,172
8:00, 9:00.

1135
01:28:20,255 --> 01:28:22,966
[ Italian ]

1136
01:28:23,050 --> 01:28:27,471
We'd both taken on, uh,
far too many drinks.

1137
01:28:27,513 --> 01:28:32,101
But it was dark. It was certainly dark
when l-- when I walked him to his car.

1138
01:28:32,184 --> 01:28:35,145
So he drove away,
and, uh, you did what ?

1139
01:28:35,187 --> 01:28:38,273
- I went to bed.
- [ Italian ]

1140
01:28:38,357 --> 01:28:43,028
Freddie's a big man, but I'm in trouble
after a couple of drinks.

1141
01:28:43,112 --> 01:28:46,490
I've been suffering all--

1142
01:28:46,532 --> 01:28:48,617
Who found him ?

1143
01:28:48,700 --> 01:28:51,286
[ Italian ]
You understand, I must ask you...

1144
01:28:51,370 --> 01:28:53,914
to stay in Rome,
Signor Greenleaf.

1145
01:28:53,997 --> 01:28:57,334
Yes, if it's gonna help,
certainly.

1146
01:28:57,376 --> 01:29:01,171
So, the doctor, he has to make
the, um--

1147
01:29:01,255 --> 01:29:04,591
- [ Italian ]
- [ Italian ]

1148
01:29:04,675 --> 01:29:07,886
- Postmortem.
- Yeah, exactly.

1149
01:29:07,970 --> 01:29:10,639
But, you know,
his first conclusion...

1150
01:29:10,723 --> 01:29:15,769
was that Signor Miles was killed
not later than 7:00 yesterday evening.

1151
01:29:15,853 --> 01:29:19,231
Well, he certainly wasn't dead
when he drove away in his car.

1152
01:29:21,358 --> 01:29:23,277
No.

1153
01:29:23,360 --> 01:29:25,279
[ Chattering ]

1154
01:29:41,044 --> 01:29:43,338
[ Italian ]

1155
01:29:48,594 --> 01:29:51,096
[ Italian ]
It's okay.

1156
01:29:51,180 --> 01:29:53,557
- Okay ?
- Si, si.

1157
01:30:03,942 --> 01:30:07,571
- Did he kill Freddie ?
- Marge. When did you get here ?

1158
01:30:07,613 --> 01:30:10,240
Tell me the truth.
Did he kill Freddie ?

1159
01:30:10,324 --> 01:30:13,869
I'd swear he didn't.
Of course he didn't.

1160
01:30:13,952 --> 01:30:18,165
I tried again.
Waiting here, watching for him.

1161
01:30:18,248 --> 01:30:21,835
Instead, it's you.
Whenever I look for Dickie, I find you.

1162
01:30:23,754 --> 01:30:26,715
What happened to your face ?

1163
01:30:26,799 --> 01:30:28,759
Dickie--
Dickie did it.

1164
01:30:28,801 --> 01:30:31,053
- Dickie ?
- My face. There was an argument.

1165
01:30:31,136 --> 01:30:33,806
I-- I said some things
I shouldn't have said and l--

1166
01:30:33,889 --> 01:30:37,518
About you. About the appalling way
he's treating you, all of us.

1167
01:30:37,601 --> 01:30:39,895
And the next thing I know,
he's launched himself at me.

1168
01:30:39,978 --> 01:30:42,106
- Are you getting on ?
- What ?

1169
01:30:42,147 --> 01:30:44,316
Get on.
I'll take you to him.

1170
01:31:08,799 --> 01:31:11,635
[ Italian ]

1171
01:31:24,189 --> 01:31:26,108
[ Engine Stops ]

1172
01:31:28,819 --> 01:31:31,029
- Where does he live ?
- We passed it a few blocks back.

1173
01:31:31,113 --> 01:31:33,532
It's where the police were.
The Palazzo Gioia.

1174
01:31:35,534 --> 01:31:38,537
Look, they don't even know I'm in Rome,
and I'm not gonna incriminate Dickie.

1175
01:31:38,579 --> 01:31:40,622
Well, perhaps
I shouldn't go either.

1176
01:31:40,706 --> 01:31:44,334
No. Well, go if you want to, but just
don't talk to the police about my face.

1177
01:31:44,376 --> 01:31:47,755
If they know he hit me and his temper,
then he could've hit Freddie.

1178
01:31:47,838 --> 01:31:49,798
I'll catch up
with you later.

1179
01:31:54,053 --> 01:31:55,846
[ Engine Starts ]

1180
01:32:08,025 --> 01:32:10,986
[ Italian ]
Signor Greenleaf !

1181
01:32:11,070 --> 01:32:13,655
It's Signor Greenleaf !
Presto, presto !

1182
01:32:13,739 --> 01:32:16,325
[ Shouting in Italian ]

1183
01:32:19,119 --> 01:32:21,330
Open the door !

1184
01:32:21,413 --> 01:32:23,791
Open up !

1185
01:32:23,874 --> 01:32:26,126
- [ Italian ]
- I live here !

1186
01:32:27,294 --> 01:32:29,254
Mr. Greenleaf !

1187
01:32:30,589 --> 01:32:32,800
Can we go up ?
Do you mind ?

1188
01:32:32,883 --> 01:32:35,469
Of course.
What happened to your face ?

1189
01:32:35,552 --> 01:32:39,223
My scooter. I fell off
getting chased by photographers.

1190
01:32:39,306 --> 01:32:43,352
The telephone, the press,
I've been-- I'm feeling hounded.

1191
01:32:43,435 --> 01:32:45,562
Do you think you could
not give out my address ?

1192
01:32:45,604 --> 01:32:50,234
Never. We've had many requests,
and we say no, even to your fiancÚe.

1193
01:32:50,317 --> 01:32:52,277
I really don't want
to see anybody.

1194
01:32:52,319 --> 01:32:55,114
- Even your fiancÚe ?
- Even her.

1195
01:32:55,155 --> 01:32:58,117
[Man Speaking Italian]

1196
01:32:58,200 --> 01:33:01,412
- What about Thomas Ripley ?
- What about Tom Ripley ?

1197
01:33:03,414 --> 01:33:05,416
You and Signor Ripley went to San Remo.
Is that right ?

1198
01:33:05,457 --> 01:33:08,585
Yes, we-- We went to San Remo.
That was months ago.

1199
01:33:08,669 --> 01:33:10,838
November, I thought.
Was it ?

1200
01:33:10,921 --> 01:33:14,466
- Did you speak to Tom ?
- November 7 is my information.

1201
01:33:14,550 --> 01:33:17,302
I donĺt remember
the exact date.

1202
01:33:17,344 --> 01:33:21,807
- When did you last see Signor Ripley ?
- A few days ago.

1203
01:33:21,849 --> 01:33:25,436
- Does he stay with you here ?
- No.

1204
01:33:25,519 --> 01:33:27,896
No.

1205
01:33:29,273 --> 01:33:32,234
Here is a pattern.
Two days ago,

1206
01:33:32,317 --> 01:33:35,279
Freddie Miles is dead,
hmm ?

1207
01:33:36,530 --> 01:33:38,991
He leaves your apartment,

1208
01:33:40,075 --> 01:33:42,828
and he's murdered.

1209
01:33:42,911 --> 01:33:48,041
Yesterday, a little boat
is found in San Remo full of rocks.

1210
01:33:48,125 --> 01:33:53,005
And the owner tells the police
it was stolen on November 7.

1211
01:33:53,047 --> 01:33:55,549
We look at hotel records...

1212
01:33:55,632 --> 01:33:58,427
and we see...

1213
01:33:58,510 --> 01:34:01,680
Dickie Greenleaf
is staying in San Remo.

1214
01:34:01,764 --> 01:34:05,517
And then our boatman remembers
two Americans taking a boat.

1215
01:34:05,601 --> 01:34:08,395
That is not a pattern.
That's a coincidence.

1216
01:34:08,479 --> 01:34:10,439
There must be 50 hotels
in San Remo.

1217
01:34:10,522 --> 01:34:13,358
There were probably a hundred people
renting a boat that day.

1218
01:34:13,400 --> 01:34:15,903
Thirty-one people.

1219
01:34:15,986 --> 01:34:17,988
Thirty-one people.

1220
01:34:19,114 --> 01:34:21,033
Thirty-one, yeah.

1221
01:34:21,116 --> 01:34:23,202
[ Italian ]

1222
01:34:23,285 --> 01:34:25,871
- Marge Sherwood.
- That is Miss Sherwood now.

1223
01:34:34,630 --> 01:34:36,673
Let her in.

1224
01:34:36,715 --> 01:34:39,385
Let her in.
What's the difference ? Let her in.

1225
01:34:41,845 --> 01:34:45,265
No ! Actually--
Actually, no.

1226
01:34:45,349 --> 01:34:48,227
I would-- I would
really appreciate it...

1227
01:34:48,310 --> 01:34:51,188
if you would ask Miss Sherwood
to come back later.

1228
01:34:53,190 --> 01:34:55,651
[ Italian ]

1229
01:34:55,734 --> 01:34:58,570
Thank you.

1230
01:34:58,654 --> 01:35:02,241
May I ask you--

1231
01:35:02,324 --> 01:35:05,869
Why would you speak to your friend
and not your fiancÚe ?

1232
01:35:05,953 --> 01:35:09,289
Well, l--
I think I just said.

1233
01:35:09,373 --> 01:35:12,709
Um, Mr. Ripley was
handling some business for me.

1234
01:35:12,751 --> 01:35:15,379
Nor does Mr. Ripley
want to marry me...

1235
01:35:15,462 --> 01:35:19,508
and ask me every single day
if I'll marry him and when.

1236
01:35:20,676 --> 01:35:22,678
Do you keep a photograph
of Signor Ripley ?

1237
01:35:22,761 --> 01:35:26,598
I'm not in the habit of carrying
around photographs of my male friends.

1238
01:35:28,267 --> 01:35:30,185
Now I think I've upset you.

1239
01:35:30,269 --> 01:35:33,397
Sorry. My English,
perhaps, is coarse.

1240
01:35:33,439 --> 01:35:35,941
It is a little coarse,
yes.

1241
01:35:39,445 --> 01:35:41,363
I'm sorry.

1242
01:35:41,447 --> 01:35:46,410
But you-- No one has seen
Signor Ripley since San Remo.

1243
01:35:46,493 --> 01:35:48,454
- I have.
- You have, yes.

1244
01:35:48,495 --> 01:35:51,248
And so has Miss Sherwood.
Ask her. And, um,

1245
01:35:51,290 --> 01:35:56,420
if I can remember the name
of the hotel he was staying at--

1246
01:35:56,503 --> 01:35:59,548
Um, the Goldoni.
Tom was staying at the Goldoni.

1247
01:35:59,631 --> 01:36:03,010
Goldoni. The Goldoni.
Good, good, but--

1248
01:36:03,093 --> 01:36:05,637
Yes, you are right.

1249
01:36:05,721 --> 01:36:07,973
You are right.
A coincidence.

1250
01:36:08,057 --> 01:36:09,975
[Siren Wailing, Distant]

1251
01:36:10,059 --> 01:36:13,645
[ Sighing ] I look forward
to our next meeting.

1252
01:36:13,729 --> 01:36:15,731
Hmm ? When I will be
more careful with my English.

1253
01:36:15,814 --> 01:36:20,069
[Roverini] Ah. I have a witness
who thinks they saw two men...

1254
01:36:20,152 --> 01:36:22,071
getting into Mr. Miles' car.

1255
01:36:22,154 --> 01:36:26,033
And she wants to identify you
in a confronto.

1256
01:36:26,116 --> 01:36:28,619
Lineup. Tomorrow, then ?

1257
01:36:30,120 --> 01:36:32,039
Uh, tomorrow.

1258
01:36:33,707 --> 01:36:35,667
[ Chuckles ]

1259
01:36:39,671 --> 01:36:41,590
- Buon giorno, Miss Sherwood.
- Buon giorno.

1260
01:36:41,673 --> 01:36:45,803
He's in, but I really don't think
he wants to meet anybody.

1261
01:36:53,185 --> 01:36:55,145
[Knocking]

1262
01:37:03,195 --> 01:37:05,155
Dick ?

1263
01:37:08,617 --> 01:37:10,786
Dickie ?

1264
01:37:12,329 --> 01:37:14,248
I know you can hear me.

1265
01:37:20,129 --> 01:37:23,048
[ Sighing ]

1266
01:37:23,090 --> 01:37:26,385
I was gonna say that I would count to
three, and if you didn't open the door--

1267
01:37:26,468 --> 01:37:30,723
But I won't count anymore.

1268
01:37:30,806 --> 01:37:32,808
On you.

1269
01:37:34,852 --> 01:37:38,355
I won't count on you
anymore.

1270
01:37:41,817 --> 01:37:46,739
Whatever it is you've done
or haven't done,

1271
01:37:46,780 --> 01:37:49,283
you've broken my heart.

1272
01:37:51,535 --> 01:37:53,954
That's one thing
I know you're guilty of.

1273
01:38:01,545 --> 01:38:03,964
And I don't know why.
[ Sobbing ]

1274
01:38:06,467 --> 01:38:09,887
I don't know why.
I just don't know why.

1275
01:38:11,638 --> 01:38:13,599
[Footsteps Receding]

1276
01:38:15,309 --> 01:38:17,311
[Typewriter Keys Clattering]

1277
01:38:17,394 --> 01:38:19,521
[Thunder Rumbling]

1278
01:38:19,730 --> 01:38:21,940
[Tom's Voice]
My dear Tom.

1279
01:38:22,024 --> 01:38:25,569
Iĺm getting out of this.

1280
01:38:25,611 --> 01:38:29,156
Freddie's death. Silvana.

1281
01:38:29,239 --> 01:38:33,452
Iĺve thought about going to the police,
but I canĺt do it.

1282
01:38:33,494 --> 01:38:35,871
I canĺt face it.

1283
01:38:35,954 --> 01:38:37,623
I canĺt face anything anymore.

1284
01:38:37,623 --> 01:38:38,707
I canĺt face anything anymore.

1285
01:38:38,791 --> 01:38:41,543
I wish I could give you
the life I took for granted.

1286
01:38:41,627 --> 01:38:44,546
[Typewriter Bell Dings,
Clattering Continues]

1287
01:38:44,630 --> 01:38:47,174
You've always understood
whatĺs at the heart of me, Tom.

1288
01:38:47,257 --> 01:38:50,636
Marge never could.

1289
01:38:50,677 --> 01:38:54,098
I suppose that's why
Iĺm writing this to you,

1290
01:38:54,139 --> 01:38:56,767
the brother I never had.

1291
01:38:56,850 --> 01:38:59,603
The only true friend
I ever had.

1292
01:39:05,275 --> 01:39:07,194
in all kinds of ways,

1293
01:39:07,277 --> 01:39:11,573
you're much more like the son
my father wanted.

1294
01:39:11,657 --> 01:39:14,868
I realize you can
change the people,

1295
01:39:14,952 --> 01:39:17,454
change the scenery,

1296
01:39:17,496 --> 01:39:19,706
but you can't change
your own rotten self.

1297
01:39:22,501 --> 01:39:25,254
Now I can't think what to do
or where to go.

1298
01:39:27,339 --> 01:39:31,927
Iĺm haunted by everything
Iĺve done and canĺt undo.

1299
01:39:33,512 --> 01:39:35,472
Iĺm sorry.

1300
01:39:37,558 --> 01:39:40,936
Iĺve made a mess of being
Dickie Greenleaf, haven't I ?

1301
01:40:45,292 --> 01:40:48,295
Tom !

1302
01:40:50,464 --> 01:40:53,759
I'll see you over there !

1303
01:40:54,927 --> 01:40:57,304
[Bell Tolling]

1304
01:41:02,142 --> 01:41:04,436
I'm so sorry to put you
through this, Peter.

1305
01:41:04,520 --> 01:41:08,107
I just can't face going to the police
by myself when my Italian's so rotten.

1306
01:41:08,190 --> 01:41:10,192
Don't be so daft.
It's fine.

1307
01:41:10,275 --> 01:41:12,903
I'm delighted you finally
made it to Venice.

1308
01:41:12,986 --> 01:41:15,614
I'm delighted, contrary to rumor,
that you're still in one piece.

1309
01:41:15,697 --> 01:41:17,699
- What rumor ?
- Oh, you know.

1310
01:41:17,783 --> 01:41:21,203
That Dickie murdered you
and is traveling under your passport.

1311
01:41:21,286 --> 01:41:23,372
I know. It's ridiculous.

1312
01:41:26,291 --> 01:41:28,377
[Man Shouting in Italian]

1313
01:41:29,503 --> 01:41:31,463
[ Shouting Continues ]

1314
01:41:31,505 --> 01:41:34,466
[Phone Ringing]

1315
01:41:38,220 --> 01:41:40,139
Welcome to Venice.

1316
01:41:40,222 --> 01:41:43,267
God, this place reeks, doesn't it ?
Can you smell it ?

1317
01:41:43,308 --> 01:41:47,187
Anyway, I've got to
the bottom of the delay, finally.

1318
01:41:47,271 --> 01:41:50,190
We're waiting
for someone from Rome.

1319
01:41:50,274 --> 01:41:52,609
What do you mean ?
They've sent for someone from Rome ?

1320
01:41:52,651 --> 01:41:55,779
- Well, yes. That's good, isn't it ?
- No, I thought...

1321
01:41:55,863 --> 01:41:59,241
that didn't happen in Italy,
that each region is separate.

1322
01:41:59,324 --> 01:42:01,744
I was sure that--
I've read that--

1323
01:42:01,827 --> 01:42:04,663
You've read the papers.
You know what a big deal it's been.

1324
01:42:04,747 --> 01:42:07,791
- American tourist murdered.
- Actually, can we not do this now ?

1325
01:42:07,875 --> 01:42:11,962
- The stench really is--
- [Man Speaking Italian]

1326
01:42:14,673 --> 01:42:18,761
[ Italian ]

1327
01:42:25,350 --> 01:42:29,188
[ Continues in Italian ]

1328
01:42:29,229 --> 01:42:33,859
He's taken over the case, 'cause they're
annoyed that the previous chap...

1329
01:42:33,942 --> 01:42:36,820
let Dickie disappear
when he was, um,

1330
01:42:36,862 --> 01:42:38,864
the only suspect
in Freddieĺs murder.

1331
01:42:38,947 --> 01:42:41,867
[ Italian ]

1332
01:42:41,909 --> 01:42:45,204
In Rome,
about three weeks ago.

1333
01:42:45,245 --> 01:42:47,206
I knew that one.

1334
01:42:47,247 --> 01:42:51,335
Um--
[ Italian ]

1335
01:42:51,377 --> 01:42:54,380
[ Italian ]

1336
01:42:54,421 --> 01:42:59,259
Are you a homosexual ?
Interesting non sequitur.

1337
01:42:59,343 --> 01:43:01,345
No.

1338
01:43:01,428 --> 01:43:04,681
- No.
- Oh.

1339
01:43:04,723 --> 01:43:09,645
By the way, um, officially
there are no Italian homosexuals.

1340
01:43:09,728 --> 01:43:12,231
Makes Michelangelo and
Leonardo very inconvenient.

1341
01:43:12,314 --> 01:43:14,024
Eh ?

1342
01:43:14,066 --> 01:43:17,277
Tell him...
I have a fiancÚe.

1343
01:43:17,361 --> 01:43:19,738
And Dickie has a fiancÚe.

1344
01:43:19,780 --> 01:43:23,409
And that Freddie Miles
probably had a string of them.

1345
01:43:23,492 --> 01:43:25,911
[ Italian ]

1346
01:43:35,087 --> 01:43:38,966
Mamma mia.
[ Italian ]

1347
01:43:39,049 --> 01:43:42,469
- [Inspector Laughing]
- [ Chuckling ]

1348
01:43:42,553 --> 01:43:44,763
- What did he say ?
- He says "so many fiancÚes."

1349
01:43:44,847 --> 01:43:48,600
[ Italian ]

1350
01:43:49,935 --> 01:43:52,938
Heĺs asking... if you
killed Freddie Miles...

1351
01:43:52,980 --> 01:43:54,940
and then killed Dickie Greenleaf.

1352
01:43:54,982 --> 01:43:58,944
No ! No, I did not kill Freddie Miles
and then kill Dickie Greenleaf.

1353
01:43:59,027 --> 01:44:02,239
Is he accusing me ?
Ask him if he's accusingme.

1354
01:44:02,281 --> 01:44:05,075
The way it works here,
it's better to be less volatile.

1355
01:44:05,117 --> 01:44:07,286
- But itĺs absurd!
- [ Italian ]

1356
01:44:07,369 --> 01:44:09,288
[ Italian ]

1357
01:44:15,627 --> 01:44:19,548
[ Italian ]

1358
01:44:22,801 --> 01:44:27,264
They found this
in Dickie's place in Rome.

1359
01:44:27,347 --> 01:44:29,933
- You opened this ?
- Of course.

1360
01:44:46,241 --> 01:44:49,078
It's a suicide note.

1361
01:44:52,873 --> 01:44:56,752
You asked me all these questions and you
already read this suicide note ?

1362
01:45:15,104 --> 01:45:17,189
I don't believe that letter.
Do you ?

1363
01:45:17,272 --> 01:45:20,818
Dickie's letter.
Do you believe it ?

1364
01:45:20,859 --> 01:45:23,320
I don't know
what to believe.

1365
01:45:23,362 --> 01:45:28,075
Can you imagine, though, if he did
kill Freddie, what that must be like ?

1366
01:45:28,200 --> 01:45:32,037
Just to wake up every morning.
I mean, how can you ?

1367
01:45:32,121 --> 01:45:35,582
Just wake up and be a person ?
Drink your coffee.

1368
01:45:35,666 --> 01:45:40,087
Well, whatever you do,
however terrible, however hurtful,

1369
01:45:40,129 --> 01:45:43,465
it all makes sense,
doesn't it, in your head.

1370
01:45:43,507 --> 01:45:46,301
You never meet anybody
who thinks they're a bad person.

1371
01:45:46,343 --> 01:45:50,389
No, I know, but you're still tormented.
You must be. You've killed someone.

1372
01:45:50,472 --> 01:45:53,600
Don't you just take the past
and put it in a room in the basement,

1373
01:45:53,684 --> 01:45:55,644
and lock the door
and never go in there ?

1374
01:45:55,728 --> 01:45:59,106
- That's what I do.
- God, yes.

1375
01:45:59,148 --> 01:46:03,819
But, of course, in my case,
it's probably a whole building.

1376
01:46:03,861 --> 01:46:06,905
-  [ Piano: Stops ]
- And then you meet someone special,

1377
01:46:06,989 --> 01:46:11,034
and all you want to do
is toss them the key.

1378
01:46:12,369 --> 01:46:14,955
Say "Open up. Step inside."

1379
01:46:17,666 --> 01:46:19,877
But you can't...

1380
01:46:19,960 --> 01:46:22,713
- [Resumes]
- because it's dark...

1381
01:46:22,796 --> 01:46:25,674
and there are demons.

1382
01:46:26,717 --> 01:46:29,178
And if anybody saw
how ugly it is--

1383
01:46:33,891 --> 01:46:35,934
Now that's the music talking.

1384
01:46:38,187 --> 01:46:41,523
It's harder to be bleak if youĺre
playing "Knees Up, Mother Brown."

1385
01:46:47,237 --> 01:46:50,199
I keep wanting to do that.

1386
01:46:50,282 --> 01:46:54,161
Fling...
the door open.

1387
01:46:54,203 --> 01:46:56,455
[Resumes]

1388
01:46:56,538 --> 01:47:00,292
Just let the light in,
clean everything out.

1389
01:47:02,586 --> 01:47:06,590
If I could take a giant eraser
and rub out everything,

1390
01:47:06,673 --> 01:47:09,593
starting with myself--

1391
01:47:12,179 --> 01:47:15,391
The thing is, Peter, if--

1392
01:47:17,935 --> 01:47:21,563
- Hmm ?
- If--

1393
01:47:23,399 --> 01:47:25,359
If--

1394
01:47:32,408 --> 01:47:34,743
No key, huh ?

1395
01:47:34,827 --> 01:47:37,538
[Boy Singing in Latin]

1396
01:47:49,466 --> 01:47:52,428
[ Continues ]

1397
01:48:19,163 --> 01:48:21,165
- Marge.
- Peter.

1398
01:48:23,625 --> 01:48:25,586
- So good to see you.
- Hello, Marge.

1399
01:48:25,627 --> 01:48:27,838
Tom.

1400
01:48:27,921 --> 01:48:31,967
- I see you found Peter.
- I think we sort of found each other.

1401
01:48:32,051 --> 01:48:35,763
- Where's Dickie's father ?
- He's not coming till the morning.

1402
01:48:35,846 --> 01:48:39,391
Evidently his stomach. I don't think
the food here is agreeing with him.

1403
01:48:39,475 --> 01:48:41,393
Oh, I was looking forward
to seeing him.

1404
01:48:41,477 --> 01:48:44,188
Dickie hasn't killed himself.
I'm sure of that.

1405
01:48:44,271 --> 01:48:46,815
There's a private detective
on the case now.

1406
01:48:46,899 --> 01:48:49,401
A Mr. MacCarron
Dickie's father's employed.

1407
01:48:49,485 --> 01:48:52,821
- That's a terrific idea.
- He's American.

1408
01:48:52,905 --> 01:48:56,241
He's already discovered
that Dickie cashed checks for $1 ,000...

1409
01:48:56,325 --> 01:48:58,494
the day before
he disappeared.

1410
01:48:58,577 --> 01:49:00,496
[ Man ]
Signora.

1411
01:49:00,579 --> 01:49:03,999
Is that what you do
before you jump into the Tiber ?

1412
01:49:04,083 --> 01:49:06,668
I donĺt think so.

1413
01:49:10,506 --> 01:49:12,716
- Is this you ?
- No, it's Tom's.

1414
01:49:12,800 --> 01:49:14,718
Splendid, eh ?

1415
01:49:14,802 --> 01:49:18,138
Golly.
Who's paying for this ?

1416
01:49:18,180 --> 01:49:20,182
Peter found it for me.

1417
01:49:20,224 --> 01:49:25,145
I can afford it because
it's damp and... falling down.

1418
01:49:25,187 --> 01:49:28,357
- Tom's transformed it.
- This is spectacular.

1419
01:49:28,440 --> 01:49:30,692
That's why
Tom wanted you to stay.

1420
01:49:30,776 --> 01:49:33,362
It's better than trying
to squeeze into my room.

1421
01:49:33,445 --> 01:49:35,531
And I know
how you hate hotels.

1422
01:49:35,614 --> 01:49:37,616
A hotel would have been fine.

1423
01:49:41,078 --> 01:49:45,624
We'll have to tell Mr. Greenleaf
how far his dollar stretched.

1424
01:49:49,002 --> 01:49:52,005
- [ Chuckles ]
- What's funny ?

1425
01:49:52,089 --> 01:49:55,634
I was just thinking about when
Tom first came to Mongibello.

1426
01:49:57,678 --> 01:50:01,140
- And look at you now.
- Look at me what ?

1427
01:50:02,391 --> 01:50:04,393
To the manor born.

1428
01:50:06,395 --> 01:50:08,564
[Bell Tolling]

1429
01:50:18,532 --> 01:50:20,743
[Tom]
Mr. Greenleaf?

1430
01:50:20,784 --> 01:50:24,580
[Continues]

1431
01:50:24,621 --> 01:50:26,582
Mr. Greenleaf?

1432
01:50:26,623 --> 01:50:30,335
Tom. How are you ?
You look well.

1433
01:50:30,419 --> 01:50:33,255
- Thank you, sir. I am well.
- Far cry from New York.

1434
01:50:33,297 --> 01:50:35,799
- Yes, it is.
- Marge.

1435
01:50:35,883 --> 01:50:38,927
Good morning.
Unusual weather.

1436
01:50:39,011 --> 01:50:41,889
- Very.
- And you, sir. Any better ?

1437
01:50:41,930 --> 01:50:45,059
Pretty good.
Sticking with hot water.

1438
01:50:45,142 --> 01:50:47,436
- Where's Mr. MacCarron ?
- San Remo.

1439
01:50:47,519 --> 01:50:50,272
The police are amateurs.

1440
01:50:50,314 --> 01:50:54,860
Well, my boy, it's come
to a pretty pass, hasn't it ?

1441
01:50:54,943 --> 01:50:58,113
What is the detective
hoping to find in San Remo ?

1442
01:50:58,197 --> 01:51:03,035
Heĺs being thorough.
Iĺm learning about my son, Tom.

1443
01:51:03,118 --> 01:51:06,538
Now he's missing,
I'm learning a great deal about him,

1444
01:51:06,622 --> 01:51:09,708
and I hope that you can
fill in some more blanks for me.

1445
01:51:09,792 --> 01:51:12,836
Marge has been good enough
to do that about Mongibello.

1446
01:51:12,920 --> 01:51:16,715
I'll try my best, sir. Obviously,
I'll do anything to help Dickie.

1447
01:51:16,799 --> 01:51:19,259
-[Continues]
- Good. This theory,

1448
01:51:19,343 --> 01:51:21,470
the letter
he left for you.

1449
01:51:21,553 --> 01:51:24,807
The police think that's
a clear indication...

1450
01:51:24,890 --> 01:51:28,644
he was planning on doing something,
uh, to himself.

1451
01:51:28,685 --> 01:51:31,480
I just don't believe that.

1452
01:51:31,563 --> 01:51:34,108
You don't want to, dear.

1453
01:51:37,319 --> 01:51:39,321
I'd like
to talk to Tom alone.

1454
01:51:39,405 --> 01:51:42,199
Perhaps this afternoon.
Would you mind?

1455
01:51:44,660 --> 01:51:48,664
Marge, what a man may say
to his sweetheart...

1456
01:51:48,747 --> 01:51:50,916
and what he'll admit
to another fellow--

1457
01:51:54,211 --> 01:51:56,922
Such as ?

1458
01:51:57,005 --> 01:52:00,551
[Continues]

1459
01:52:00,634 --> 01:52:03,887
[ Clears Throat ]
What a waste of lives and opportunities.

1460
01:52:03,971 --> 01:52:06,974
I'd pay that fellow a hundred dollars
right now to shut up !

1461
01:52:15,315 --> 01:52:18,694
No, Marge doesn't
know the half of it.

1462
01:52:18,736 --> 01:52:22,030
And his passport photo.

1463
01:52:22,072 --> 01:52:24,950
Did you hear ? To scratch out
his own face like that ?

1464
01:52:25,075 --> 01:52:27,202
Can you imagine ?

1465
01:52:27,286 --> 01:52:30,539
Frame of mind
you'd have to be in ?

1466
01:52:30,622 --> 01:52:33,917
"I've thought about going to the police,
but I can't face it.

1467
01:52:34,001 --> 01:52:37,546
I can't face
anything anymore."

1468
01:52:37,588 --> 01:52:40,924
I feel guilty. I feel
like I pushed him away.

1469
01:52:41,008 --> 01:52:43,052
I feel like I spoke
and he heard you.

1470
01:52:43,135 --> 01:52:45,929
Well,
[ Clears Throat ]

1471
01:52:46,013 --> 01:52:48,599
if we all pushed him away,
what about him pushing us away ?

1472
01:52:48,682 --> 01:52:51,268
You've been a great friend
to my son.

1473
01:52:51,351 --> 01:52:54,480
Everything is
someone else's fault.

1474
01:52:54,563 --> 01:52:57,024
We all want to sow
wild oats,

1475
01:52:57,107 --> 01:53:00,402
but somebody's got to--
got to--

1476
01:53:00,486 --> 01:53:03,280
What is the word ?

1477
01:53:03,363 --> 01:53:06,575
You know, the moment
someone confronts him,

1478
01:53:07,951 --> 01:53:10,454
he lashes out.

1479
01:53:10,537 --> 01:53:13,082
He always has.

1480
01:53:13,165 --> 01:53:17,044
You know, people always say
that you can't choose your parents,

1481
01:53:21,799 --> 01:53:24,259
but you can't choose
your children.

1482
01:53:25,636 --> 01:53:29,223
- [Knocking]
- [Freddie's Voice] Dickie.

1483
01:53:29,306 --> 01:53:32,893
[Dickie's Voice] You can be a leech.
You can be quite boring.

1484
01:53:32,976 --> 01:53:34,895
- [Tom's Voice] Stop it !
- [Dickie's Voice] It's boring.

1485
01:53:34,978 --> 01:53:38,899
- [Knocking]
- [ Voices Overlapping, indistinct]

1486
01:53:38,982 --> 01:53:41,318
[Tom Screaming]
Stop, stop, stop !

1487
01:53:42,820 --> 01:53:44,738
- Stop, stop, stop !
- [Freddie's Voice] Tommy, Tommy.

1488
01:53:44,822 --> 01:53:46,740
[Dickie's Voice]
Like a little girl.

1489
01:53:46,824 --> 01:53:49,910
- Like a little girl.
- [Knocking]

1490
01:53:49,993 --> 01:53:51,829
[Knocking]

1491
01:53:53,539 --> 01:53:55,499
- [Knocking]
- Coming.

1492
01:53:55,582 --> 01:53:57,960
- Sorry. I was asleep.
- Finally.

1493
01:53:58,001 --> 01:54:00,129
- I must have fallen asleep.
- Did Dickie's dad go ?

1494
01:54:00,212 --> 01:54:02,172
You look ghastly, Tom.
Did you have a nightmare ?

1495
01:54:02,214 --> 01:54:05,426
- He's having an early night.
- Oh, poor man.

1496
01:54:05,509 --> 01:54:07,970
You know, we were banging
on that door forever.

1497
01:54:11,557 --> 01:54:13,517
[Marge]
Uh-oh.

1498
01:54:13,559 --> 01:54:17,146
- I think I've broken a strap.
- Not guilty.

1499
01:54:17,229 --> 01:54:20,190
- I'll fix some drinks.
- [ Marge Giggling ]

1500
01:54:20,274 --> 01:54:22,901
Ah !
You walk in Venice.

1501
01:54:24,445 --> 01:54:26,363
Are you okay ?

1502
01:54:27,865 --> 01:54:29,700
I'm fine.

1503
01:54:29,783 --> 01:54:33,954
- Did you want me to stick around ?
- No, it's okay.

1504
01:54:35,998 --> 01:54:38,167
I could come back.

1505
01:54:53,515 --> 01:54:55,642
Your key.

1506
01:54:59,354 --> 01:55:02,024
- [Knocking At Door]
- [Marge] Tom ?

1507
01:55:02,107 --> 01:55:05,611
Marge, I'm in the bath.
I won't be long.

1508
01:55:05,694 --> 01:55:07,905
Tom, I have to speak to you.
Itĺs urgent.

1509
01:55:11,658 --> 01:55:13,577
Coming.

1510
01:55:25,089 --> 01:55:28,384
- I found Dickie's rings.
- What ?

1511
01:55:28,467 --> 01:55:30,469
You have Dickie's rings.

1512
01:55:35,265 --> 01:55:37,184
I can explain.

1513
01:55:37,267 --> 01:55:39,937
Dickie promised me he would
never take off this ring.

1514
01:55:40,020 --> 01:55:43,065
Let me put some clothes on
and we'll talk about this.

1515
01:55:43,148 --> 01:55:45,567
- I have to tell Mr. Greenleaf.
- Marge, you're being hysterical.

1516
01:55:45,651 --> 01:55:49,113
He promised me, "I swear, I will never
take off this ring until we get--"

1517
01:55:49,196 --> 01:55:51,115
- Shut up !
- [ Gasping ]

1518
01:55:53,325 --> 01:55:56,787
I'm wet, Marge.
I've lost my towel.

1519
01:55:56,870 --> 01:55:59,873
And Iĺd really like
to put some clothes on.

1520
01:55:59,957 --> 01:56:01,959
Go and pour us both a drink.

1521
01:56:05,379 --> 01:56:07,297
Pour us a drink.

1522
01:56:40,664 --> 01:56:43,000
Marge ?

1523
01:56:43,083 --> 01:56:45,335
Where are you going ?

1524
01:56:45,419 --> 01:56:48,881
I wasn't snooping.
I just--

1525
01:56:48,964 --> 01:56:51,884
I was looking for a needle
and thread to mend my bra.

1526
01:56:53,886 --> 01:56:57,473
That scent you're wearing.

1527
01:56:57,556 --> 01:57:00,809
I bought that
for you.

1528
01:57:00,851 --> 01:57:03,437
The thing about Dickie--

1529
01:57:03,520 --> 01:57:05,439
So many things.

1530
01:57:07,357 --> 01:57:10,944
That day when he was late
coming back from Rome,

1531
01:57:11,028 --> 01:57:12,946
I tried to tell you this.

1532
01:57:13,030 --> 01:57:16,492
He was with another girl.
I'm not talking about Meredith, either.

1533
01:57:16,575 --> 01:57:19,828
Another girl
that we met in a bar.

1534
01:57:19,870 --> 01:57:22,956
He couldn't be faithful
for five minutes.

1535
01:57:23,040 --> 01:57:25,042
So when he makes a promise,

1536
01:57:25,125 --> 01:57:27,169
it doesn't mean what it means
when you make a promise...

1537
01:57:27,252 --> 01:57:29,838
or I make a promise.

1538
01:57:29,880 --> 01:57:33,884
He has so many realities, Dickie,
and he believes them all.

1539
01:57:33,967 --> 01:57:37,179
He lies. He lies.

1540
01:57:37,221 --> 01:57:41,642
And that's his-- Half the time
he doesn't even realize he's doing it.

1541
01:57:41,725 --> 01:57:45,020
And today,

1542
01:57:45,062 --> 01:57:48,857
I really started wondering whether
he may have killed Freddie.

1543
01:57:48,941 --> 01:57:52,528
He would get so crazy
if anybody would contradict him.

1544
01:57:52,611 --> 01:57:55,322
Well, you know that.
You know that.

1545
01:57:55,406 --> 01:57:58,033
You know that.

1546
01:57:58,075 --> 01:58:00,369
And thatĺs the irony, Marge.

1547
01:58:00,411 --> 01:58:02,371
I loved you.

1548
01:58:02,413 --> 01:58:04,373
You may as well know, Marge.
I loved you.

1549
01:58:04,415 --> 01:58:07,167
I donĺt know, maybe it's
grotesque of me to say this now,

1550
01:58:07,251 --> 01:58:10,045
so just... write it on apiece
of paper or something...

1551
01:58:10,129 --> 01:58:12,589
and put it in your purse
for a rainy day.

1552
01:58:12,673 --> 01:58:16,885
"Tom loves me. Tom loves me."

1553
01:58:16,969 --> 01:58:19,346
- Why do you have Dickie's rings ?
- I told you.

1554
01:58:19,430 --> 01:58:22,516
- He gave them to me.
- Why ? When ?

1555
01:58:22,599 --> 01:58:25,602
I feel as if you haven't been listening
to anything Iĺve been saying to you.

1556
01:58:25,686 --> 01:58:28,939
I don't believe you.
I don't believe you.

1557
01:58:29,022 --> 01:58:31,358
- It's all true.
- I don't believe...

1558
01:58:31,442 --> 01:58:35,821
a single word you've said.
[ Gasping, Shuddering ]

1559
01:58:35,904 --> 01:58:38,615
You're shivering, Marge.
Look at you.

1560
01:58:38,699 --> 01:58:42,494
Marge, can I hold you ?

1561
01:58:42,578 --> 01:58:44,538
Will you let me hold you ?

1562
01:58:44,621 --> 01:58:46,665
- [ Screaming ]
- Marge ?

1563
01:58:46,790 --> 01:58:49,835
- Peter ! Thank God you're here.
- Whatĺs going on ?

1564
01:58:49,918 --> 01:58:53,255
Get me out of here.
Get me out of here. Please!

1565
01:58:53,338 --> 01:58:58,177
- [Peter] Tom, are you okay ?
- [Marge Sobbing]

1566
01:58:58,218 --> 01:59:01,346
You try.
You try talking to her.

1567
01:59:02,431 --> 01:59:04,516
- [Peter] Tom ?
- I give up.

1568
01:59:04,600 --> 01:59:07,186
Tell me whatĺs going on.
Tom !

1569
01:59:07,269 --> 01:59:09,730
- [Tom] What did I ever do to her?
- Listen--

1570
01:59:09,813 --> 01:59:12,941
Have her tell you one thing
that Iĺve ever done to her.

1571
01:59:13,025 --> 01:59:15,694
You can't be angry
with her.

1572
01:59:15,778 --> 01:59:18,739
She's confused, and she needs
someone to blame.

1573
01:59:18,781 --> 01:59:20,741
So she blames you.

1574
01:59:20,783 --> 01:59:23,369
I'll go back home
and talk to her.

1575
01:59:23,410 --> 01:59:25,913
As for you,

1576
01:59:25,996 --> 01:59:28,624
either get a safety razor
or grow a beard.

1577
01:59:37,049 --> 01:59:38,967
[Knocking]

1578
01:59:41,637 --> 01:59:44,807
- Is Mr. Greenleaf here ?
- Mr. Ripley ?

1579
01:59:44,890 --> 01:59:47,559
- Yes.
- I'm Alvin MacCarron.

1580
01:59:50,270 --> 01:59:52,940
[Marge] I donĺt know,
I donĺt know. I just know it.

1581
01:59:53,023 --> 01:59:55,943
[Mr. Greenleaf] Marge, there's female
intuition and then there are facts.

1582
01:59:58,529 --> 02:00:00,447
- Tom.
- Sir.

1583
02:00:00,531 --> 02:00:03,242
Marge, you should have waited.
I didn't--

1584
02:00:03,325 --> 02:00:05,994
Didn't Peter say Iĺd
come by and pick you up ?

1585
02:00:07,121 --> 02:00:09,748
Marge has been telling us
about the rings.

1586
02:00:09,790 --> 02:00:12,292
Yes, I feel ridiculous
I didn't mention them yesterday.

1587
02:00:12,376 --> 02:00:14,795
I clean forgot.
Ridiculous.

1588
02:00:17,381 --> 02:00:21,677
Perhaps you didn't mention them because
there's only one conclusion to be drawn.

1589
02:00:23,762 --> 02:00:27,015
Iĺm going to take Marge for a walk.
Tom, Mr. MacCarron needs to talk to you.

1590
02:00:27,099 --> 02:00:29,309
There's no need. We could go
to the bar. There's no need.

1591
02:00:29,393 --> 02:00:31,603
No, no.

1592
02:00:31,645 --> 02:00:33,939
I think you should
stay here.

1593
02:00:36,442 --> 02:00:39,611
[Door Opening, Closing]

1594
02:00:55,794 --> 02:00:58,255
I could probably
see my room from here.

1595
02:00:58,338 --> 02:01:00,299
I can see my house.

1596
02:01:02,301 --> 02:01:06,430
When you see where you live from a
distance, it's like a dream, isn't it ?

1597
02:01:06,513 --> 02:01:08,766
I don't care for B.S.

1598
02:01:08,849 --> 02:01:11,477
I don't care to hear it.
I don't care to speak it.

1599
02:01:13,687 --> 02:01:15,981
- Okay.
- Did you know that at Princeton...

1600
02:01:16,023 --> 02:01:18,358
Dickie Greenleaf
half-killed a boy ?

1601
02:01:19,443 --> 02:01:21,445
At a party over some girl.

1602
02:01:21,528 --> 02:01:25,407
Kicked the kid several times
in the head, put him in the hospital.

1603
02:01:25,491 --> 02:01:29,328
Boy had a wire fixed in his jaw,
lost some hearing.

1604
02:01:29,370 --> 02:01:32,664
Why do you think Dickie's father
sent him to Europe in the first place ?

1605
02:01:35,376 --> 02:01:39,588
The Rome police didn't think
to ask Mr. Greenleaf.

1606
02:01:39,671 --> 02:01:42,633
Nor did they think to check
on whether a Thomas Ripley...

1607
02:01:42,716 --> 02:01:45,886
had ever been a student
at Princeton University.

1608
02:01:45,969 --> 02:01:50,599
Oh, I turned up
a Tom Ripley...

1609
02:01:50,682 --> 02:01:54,770
who had been a piano tuner
in the music department.

1610
02:01:55,854 --> 02:01:57,940
You see, in America,

1611
02:01:58,023 --> 02:02:02,528
we are taught to check a fact
before it becomes a fact.

1612
02:02:02,611 --> 02:02:05,030
We're taught to nose around.

1613
02:02:05,072 --> 02:02:07,950
When a girl drowns herself,

1614
02:02:08,033 --> 02:02:10,411
find out if
that girl is pregnant.

1615
02:02:10,494 --> 02:02:13,414
Find out if Dickie
had an embarrassment there.

1616
02:02:14,832 --> 02:02:18,210
Mr. Greenleaf appreciates your loyalty.
He really does.

1617
02:02:18,252 --> 02:02:21,338
Marge--
She has a hundred theories.

1618
02:02:21,422 --> 02:02:24,341
There are a few things
that she doesn't know.

1619
02:02:24,425 --> 02:02:26,385
We hope she never knows.

1620
02:02:26,468 --> 02:02:28,721
I hope she never knows.

1621
02:02:28,762 --> 02:02:31,265
Three different people...

1622
02:02:31,348 --> 02:02:34,893
saw Dickie
get into Freddie's car.

1623
02:02:34,977 --> 02:02:38,272
One man,
who will not testify...

1624
02:02:38,355 --> 02:02:41,275
because he was jumping somebody
else's wife at the time,

1625
02:02:41,358 --> 02:02:45,362
saw Dickie removing license plates
from a red sports car.

1626
02:02:45,446 --> 02:02:49,408
The police know about this man because
he happens to be a policeman.

1627
02:02:51,452 --> 02:02:54,913
I found these in the basement
of Dickie's apartment.

1628
02:02:54,997 --> 02:02:57,082
They belong to Freddie's car.

1629
02:02:57,166 --> 02:03:01,462
Mr. Greenleaf has asked me...

1630
02:03:01,545 --> 02:03:04,423
to lose these in the canal
this evening.

1631
02:03:06,925 --> 02:03:09,553
[Bell Tolling]

1632
02:03:09,636 --> 02:03:12,473
Mr. Greenleaf feels that
there was a silent promise...

1633
02:03:12,556 --> 02:03:15,726
in Dickie's letter to you
which he intends to honor.

1634
02:03:15,809 --> 02:03:18,353
He also intends to transfer
a good portion...

1635
02:03:18,437 --> 02:03:23,150
of Dickie's income from his trust
into your name.

1636
02:03:23,233 --> 02:03:25,319
He does not intend...

1637
02:03:25,402 --> 02:03:28,864
to give the Italians any
information about Dickie's past.

1638
02:03:30,824 --> 02:03:34,620
He's rather hoping that...
you will feel the same.

1639
02:03:52,679 --> 02:03:54,598
- Thank you so much, Tom.
- Sir.

1640
02:03:54,681 --> 02:03:56,600
Good-bye.

1641
02:04:01,230 --> 02:04:05,526
Marge, I feel I never should have said
those things to you the other evening.

1642
02:04:05,609 --> 02:04:09,613
I was pretty flustered,
and the rings-- And you looked so--

1643
02:04:09,696 --> 02:04:11,990
I don't know.

1644
02:04:12,032 --> 02:04:16,120
But I hope that note goes
in your purse to New York...

1645
02:04:16,203 --> 02:04:18,664
for a rainy day.

1646
02:04:20,207 --> 02:04:23,919
- What are you gonna do now, Tom ?
- I don't know.

1647
02:04:24,002 --> 02:04:26,130
Peter has a concert in Athens
next month,

1648
02:04:26,213 --> 02:04:28,799
so he asked me to come along
and help out.

1649
02:04:31,385 --> 02:04:33,303
He says good-bye.

1650
02:04:33,387 --> 02:04:35,347
By the way, he was
in rehearsal so he couldn't--

1651
02:04:35,389 --> 02:04:39,601
Why do I think there's
never been a Ripley rainy day ?

1652
02:04:39,685 --> 02:04:42,271
What ?

1653
02:04:42,354 --> 02:04:46,066
I know it was you.
I know it was you.

1654
02:04:46,150 --> 02:04:48,986
I know it was you !
I know it was you !

1655
02:04:49,069 --> 02:04:52,698
- Marge, Marge. Please !
- I know you killed Dickie !

1656
02:04:52,781 --> 02:04:54,700
- Marge !
- I know ! No !

1657
02:04:54,783 --> 02:04:58,287
[ Sobbing ]
I know it was you !

1658
02:04:58,370 --> 02:05:00,372
Marge.
Marge, please.

1659
02:05:00,456 --> 02:05:03,125
It's not Tom.
Really.

1660
02:05:11,717 --> 02:05:14,970
[Tom And Peter]
We are called gondoleri

1661
02:05:15,054 --> 02:05:19,016
But thatĺs a vagary
Itĺs quite honorary

1662
02:05:19,224 --> 02:05:24,480
The trade that we ply

1663
02:05:24,605 --> 02:05:27,357
Ask me what I want to change
about this moment.

1664
02:05:27,441 --> 02:05:29,902
I don't know. What do you want
to change about this moment ?

1665
02:05:29,943 --> 02:05:31,653
Nothing.

1666
02:05:35,324 --> 02:05:38,118
[ Peter ]
I'm freezing. Coming down ?

1667
02:05:38,202 --> 02:05:41,038
Later. I want
to catch the sunset.

1668
02:05:41,121 --> 02:05:45,376
- You're mad. [ Chuckling ]
- I am.

1669
02:05:55,302 --> 02:05:57,221
[Meredith]
Dickie ?

1670
02:06:00,432 --> 02:06:02,351
Dickie ?

1671
